<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: Section II Executive Summary -- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>

<h2>Therapeutic Drugs and Biologics</h2>
by Henry I. Miller and William M. Wardell<P>

<CENTER><B><FONT >EXECUTIVE SUMMARY</B></FONT></B>
<BR>
</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >The goal of this proposal is to speed the delivery
of safe and effective new drugs and biologics to patients in need.
 To achieve it, the plan proposes changes in the current regulatory
system that will facilitate early clinical research, increase
the efficiency of drug development and its regulatory oversight,
and reduce the overall time and cost required for safe new drugs
to reach the market.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >The Need For Reform</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >The existing system for regulating drugs in
the United States has been fairly successful, as narrowly defined
by an assurance that products admitted to the market are reasonably
safe and effective.  By broader measures, however, it has failed.
The development and approval of new drugs and biologics is too
slow and costly.  The present system wastes the resources of both
the pharmaceutical industry and the Food and Drug Administration
(FDA). In the name of safety and effectiveness at any cost, the
development of many promising new therapies is prevented, and
the availability of new products delayed.  An unnecessary burden
is being borne by patients, by U.S. industry, and by the national
economy -- unnecessary because safety and effectiveness do not
have to be sacrificed for innovation and the introduction of greater
efficiency. We need a wiser balance of objectives.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The total time required for drug development,
from synthesis of the molecule to marketing approval, has more
than doubled -- from 6.5 to 14.8 years -- since 1964.  The time
from an Investigational New Drug (IND) filing to a New Drug Application
(NDA) approval now averages 8 years.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >FDA has raised the regulatory burden on drug
sponsors by continually introducing new requirements and policies
without due regard for their potential to hinder the delivery
of new and innovative therapies to patients who need them.  The
drug-development system in the United States has become the most
ponderous and expensive in the world.  The cost of bringing a
drug to market now averages more than $350 million. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >There has been broad consensus for nearly three
decades that reforms are necessary, but few have been implemented,
and none expeditiously or widely.  Occasional attempts by FDA
to streamline regulation are little more than window-dressing.
 The inability of the executive branch of government -- including
FDA -- to reform itself necessitates legislative action to change
the scope and procedures of oversight.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Numerous official panels and inquiries over
the past 30 years have proposed remedies for the deficiencies
of the system.  The most important and consistently repeated of
these recommendations has been the need for <I>management and
structural reforms</I> that would transfer some tasks currently
performed internally by FDA to outside experts and organizations.
 While FDA has at one time or another delegated most of its review
and evaluation functions (except final sign-off for approval)
to outside experts or entities, the delegation has been piecemeal
and disorganized; partial privatization has never been integrated
in a way that could create an efficient overall system. The plan
proposal corrects that and creates a system with these recommended
management and structural reforms at its core.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Other reforms recommended repeatedly have included
a lesser role for FDA in the scrutiny of early-phase clinical
investigations and the wider use of accelerated approvals coupled
with continued post-market surveillance.  These recommendations
are adopted, explicitly or implicitly, in the current proposal.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >The Proposal<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >While rationalizing and enhancing the efficiency
of the process for developing, reviewing, and approving new drugs
and biologics,<I> the proposal maintains the existing legal requirement
for pre-market demonstration of safety and effectiveness</I>.
 Preserved as well are FDA's enforcement powers and the agency's
authority to issue the final sign-off approval for product marketing.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The key changes are these:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >1) Primary responsibility for managing the
Investigational New Drug (IND) filing, oversight of the clinical
program, and New Drug Application (NDA)/Product License Application
(PLA) review will be transferred from FDA to Drug Certification
Bodies (DCBs).  The DCBs, which can be private- or public-sector
(university) organizations, for-profit or non-profit, will be
certified by FDA and staffed -- as required by the language of
the Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act -- with &quot;experts qualified
by scientific training and experience.&quot;<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >2) The sponsor will submit NDAs (or PLAs) to
the DCB, not to FDA.  After evaluating the NDA, the DCB will submit
the results of its review (if favorable) to FDA. The FDA Commissioner
will then have a finite period of time in which to accept the
DCB's recommendation for approval (which, legally, is a &quot;rebuttable
presumption&quot;) or to deny approval. If approval is denied,
at the discretion of the sponsor and the DCB, a review may be
undertaken by an independent appeals panel reporting to the Secretary
of HHS.  All parties, including the FDA, will be expected to accept
the decision of the Secretary. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >These reforms will encourage greater efficiency
and cost-effectiveness via competition among the DCBs, improvements
which will affect both the tactics and the strategy of drug development
and approval.  DCBs' competition for sponsor-clients will favor
those that perform effective problem-solving for the client, manage
the oversight and review efficiently, and perform reviews in a
timely way.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Economic pressures will encourage the DCBs
to be competent and timely, and to cultivate a reputation for
integrity -- traits that will be most highly prized by clients.
 The enormous complexity and myriad alternatives at various steps
in the drug development process provide the DCB opportunities
to add value to the client's product.  Just in the realm of clinical
trials, the choice of endpoints, indications, and trial design
strongly influences the size, time and cost of development programs;
therefore, there is significant potential for savings of time
and money.  Subject to the legal standard of safety and effectiveness,
DCBs will be encouraged to devise innovative and more efficient
ways of developing drugs and getting them approved.  This strategic
competition among DCBs and cooperation between DCBs and sponsors
will transform the drug development and approval process and redress
the current trend of increasing time and costs.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >More efficient management of the oversight
and review process will reduce the time and costs required for
drug development and approval.  In this way, greater numbers of
new drugs will become available to patients in a timelier fashion.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>

<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
