</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: Development of the Device Industry -- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>

<h3>DEVELOPMENT OF REGULATION OF THE
MEDICAL DEVICE INDUSTRY</h3>
<P>
<FONT >Close government regulation of the medical
device industry is a relatively recent phenomenon in western democracies.
In the United States, there was little regulation before 1976
aside from laws that ensured that devices performed in accordance
with their labeling<sup><a href="foot.html">9</a></sup>. In Western Europe, regulation varied from
country to country. There was little direct governmental regulation
in some countries, such as Great Britain. Even in those European
countries with a long history of regulation, such as Germany,
regulations existed largely to ensure that manufacturers met standards
which had been approved by a consensus of the relevant manufacturers
and users.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >All this radically changed in the United States
with the passage of the 1976 Medical Device Amendments to the
Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act. The law first provided for <I>general
controls</I> which would apply to all devices. This included control
of labeling (and, by extension, advertising and all other communication
between manufacturers and users) and manufacturing (and, by extension,
design) practices (GMP's- good manufacturing practices). Devices
whose safety could be assured by general controls alone were to
be placed in Class 1. The law envisioned that the Food and Drug
Administration (FDA) would devise a process to approve many hundreds
of <I>performance standards</I>. Devices whose safety could be
assured by their also adhering to such performance standards were
to be placed in Class 2. Finally, Class 3 was reserved for those
few devices which would require a case by case prospective analysis,
as their complexity precluded assurance of safety by adherence
to performance standards and general controls alone. A manufacturer
wishing to market a Class 2 device needed only to notify the FDA
90 days in advance of its intention to sell the device and document
that it met the relevant performance standards. Marketing was
permitted if the FDA did not formally object in this time frame.
Only Class 3 devices required explicit premarket approval. The
premarket approval (PMA) application was to be acted on by the
FDA in no more than 180 days.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >All existing devices (preamendment devices)
were to be temporarily approved and placed, by category, into
one of the three classes, as determined by broadly based panels.
Section 510(k) of the law allowed the manufacturer to petition
the FDA to approve a new device that was &quot;substantially equivalent&quot;
to a device manufactured before 1976 and place it into the same
class as the predicate device. It was permitted to demonstrate
that a new device was substantially equivalent to a postamendment
device which in turn was substantially equivalent to a preamendment
device. At some future date, Class 3 preamendment devices and
new devices which were approved under section 510(k) as being
<I>substantially</I> <I>equivalent</I> to Class 3 preamendment
devices were to be subject to a PMA.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Finally, new devices which were not substantially
equivalent to a preamendment device were automatically placed
in Class 3 (thus requiring premarket approval through a PMA process).
There was provision in the law for reclassification to a lower
class if it could be shown that compliance with general controls
alone, or general controls and performance standards, could ensure
safety.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The intent of this somewhat convoluted scheme
was to exercise no more governmental control than appeared necessary
and to avoid delays in introducing useful products to the market.
In fact, in the early years of device regulation, expeditious
approval was the rule.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >However, the system contained the seeds of
its own destruction. Congress and the FDA grossly underestimated
the complexity of the very heterogeneous medical device industry.
Although the formulation and approval of performance standards
were the foundation of the classification system and thus the
heart of the regulations, the FDA approved virtually no performance
standards. The reclassification process for new devices proved
so cumbersome that the FDA essentially did not implement it. 
Although Congress had provided no guidance as to how to determine
&quot;substantial equivalence,&quot; the 510(k) process was heavily
relied upon and the FDA made every effort to stretch the law to
the breaking point and accept claims of substantial equivalence
in order to allow manufactures to bring devices to the market
quickly and predictably. The FDA apparently gave little or no
thought of ever requiring PMA's for preamendment devices. In summary,
the law was &quot;working&quot; because FDA did not implement
it as written<sup><a href="foot.html">10</a></sup>.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The dissociation between the law as written
and as applied became more and more apparent throughout the 1980's,
resulting in major investigations of the FDA by congressional
oversight committees, the General Accounting Office and the Office
of Technology Assessment<sup><a href="foot.html">11</a></sup>. With the law clearly not being implemented
literally, it was easy to reap political benefits by criticizing
the operation of the FDA. Scandals at the FDA concerning generic
drugs compounded the problem and the prestige of the agency fell.
The FDA became more cautious, approval times began to lengthen
and enforcement began to take on an arbitrary character. However,
the 1976 statute, even though it was often vague and incomplete,
precluded serious governmental abuse. By 1990, Congress was ready
to act. It appears that the possibly of deregulation was not considered.
Instead, the Safe Medical Device Act of 1990 vastly increased
the power of the FDA over the device industry.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Several aspects of the 1990 act require comment.
The FDA was granted the authority to impose large civil penalties.
The act required postmarket reporting by users, distributors,
importers and manufacturers of device failures which did or might
cause harm. This requirement for redundant reporting of even the
suspicion of device failure resulted in the FDA being inundated
by more data than it could analyze or even catalog, especially
as the fear of penalties created a great incentive to complete
reports of marginal events. More fundamentally, the 510(k) process
was significantly modified. No longer could a company, even in
principle, market a device 90 days after submitting a 510(k) &quot;notification&quot;
(unless the FDA formally objected). Now the company was forbidden
to market the device until it received explicit <I>premarket</I>
permission from the FDA, in the form of a formal &quot;order.&quot;
The act defined &quot;substantial equivalence&quot;, the basis
for a 510(k) decision,  very broadly and explicitly allowed a
device to be placed in Class 2 on the basis of &quot;substantial
equivalence&quot; even if it had different technological characteristics
from its predicate device. The lack of FDA approval of performance
standards to allow for an objective approval process was implicitly
acknowledged by simply no longer requiring  them. However, these
provisions, rather than liberalizing the process, further constrained
it as the FDA was given the unlimited power to devise any &quot;special
controls&quot; that it deemed necessary for Class 2 devices. The
combination of these changes effectively removed any difference
in principle between Class 2 and Class 3 devices as now premarket
approval based on the judgement of FDA reviewers, rather that
conformity with recognized standards, was needed for both.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Further medical device amendments followed
in 1992. They were for the most part technical corrections or
provided time extension for the FDA to complete previously required
work. They did not change the essential character of the power
of the FDA.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT21-B12-10</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA074-000493-B048-35</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
