</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: State of the Device Industry -- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>
<br>
<h3>THE CURRENT STATE OF THE MEDICAL
DEVICE INDUSTRY</h3>
<P>
<FONT >After many years of healthy growth, the medical
device industry is approaching a crises. Although the difficulties
that some companies are having are the result of their inability
to adapt to the new market realities which require more cost effective
solutions, much is due to misdirected governmental policy. The
direct and indirect effects of inappropriate product liability
policies are very important but are beyond the scope of this paper.
We will concentrate here on the consequences of FDA regulation.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The time it takes to obtain FDA approval of
a new product and the perceived capriciousness of the process
is perhaps the greatest concern to industry. The 1976 law envisioned
that the 510(k) approval process should not take longer than a
total of 90 days.  It is actually quite difficult to interpret
FDA's own statistics concerning their review times. Their preference
for using median times masks the fact that the time is skewed
sharply toward long reviews. Often they cite time at the FDA rather
than total elapsed time, not counting the time the manufacturer
needs to provide additional data required by the reviewer. Finally,
the FDA may &quot;stop the clock&quot; and this may not be noted.
Although the FDA believes that only counting the time at the FDA
is &quot;fair,&quot; the essential point is that if the entire
process is slow there is a severe disincentive to the development
of products in the United States. By 1992 the <I>median</I> elapsed
time was 90 days. The median then increased to 164 days by 1993,
dropping back to 155 days by 1994.<sup><a href="foot.html">12</a></sup> However, by definition, half
the approvals take longer than the median. In 1994, 5% of the
510(k) applications were taking more than 613 days, or almost
2 years.<sup><a href="foot.html">13</a></sup>  The net result is an increase in R&amp;D costs and a
costly delay in the time needed to develop a positive cash flow.
During early 1995, it was apparent that the FDA, under extreme
political pressure from a wide variety of sources, had reassigned
resources, softened their policies and made a significant effort
to decrease review times and introduce more reason into the process.
It is difficult to predict how long this will last.  However,
it should be noted that there is now nothing in the statute that
requires or provides an incentive for  expeditious reviews<sup><a href="foot.html">14</a></sup>.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >&quot;New&quot; Class 3 devices require that
the FDA approve a PMA. The 1976 statue allowed for a 180 day period
for FDA review. In 1990, the mean total elapsed time for an FDA
decision was 609 days. By 1993 it had climbed to 823 days. This
represents an extraordinary delay and has been a principal reason
the number of PMA submissions dropped from 78 to 40 during that
period<sup><a href="foot.html">15</a></sup>.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Most PMA submissions and an increasing number
of 510(k) submissions require the generation of clinical data.
The law requires approval of clinical protocols by an Institutional
Review Board (IRB). For clinical studies posing potential hazards,
the FDA must also prospectively approve the details of the study.
There have been many anecdotal reports of long delays in such
approvals. As such clinical studies, by necessity, take place
before submission for device approval, these delays are additive
to the delays in the 510(k) and PMA approval process.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >There have been some attempts to quantify the
costs of these delays<sup><a href="foot.html">16</a></sup>. The Western European regulatory system
has been used as a benchmark. In general, our best estimate is
that European approvals require less than half the time of American
approvals. In fact, in many circumstances, European companies
which have demonstrated compliance with design and manufacturing
quality control standards can self-approve broad categories of
devices. Similarly, there is a conducive climate for clinical
investigation in many European countries. The bottom line is that
a product that might take 6 years to bring to market in the United
States might take 4 years in Europe. With this early introduction
in Europe, there is additionally a great competitive advantage
in other international markets. This necessarily means that, even
if a new product is eventually successful, venture capital will
be required for a longer time in this country and some foreign
markets may be entirely lost. The increased costs plus the uncertainties
of the regulatory process have resulted in a predictable decrease
in the availability of venture capital in the United States.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The more favorable regulatory climate in Western
Europe has allowed many companies to establish a positive cash
flow for new products by introducing the product in Europe before
marketing in the United States. Generally such a strategy can
be expected to save approximately two years. This implies that
American patients are often cared for with products several generations
behind those used for Europeans. This phenomenon is most apparent
in fast moving fields of medicine such as imaging and cardiology.
Recently, Medtronics, one of the largest U.S. device companies,
announced that it was transferring its entire venture group to
Europe. With an increase in clinical research in Europe along
with earlier product introductions, there will be an increased
incentive also to move manufacturing jobs<sup><a href="foot.html">17</a></sup>.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >While in the past American dominance in the
medical device industry was assured, the current outlook is far
less optimistic. Many factors had led to this dominance including
a well financed health care system, strong academic health centers,
a reasonable regulatory policy and low manufacturing costs. Of
these, our efficient manufacturing still gives us a distinct advantage.
Significant regulatory reform would go a long way to reverse the
current adverse trend.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT21-B12-11</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA074-000493-B048-73</DOCOLDNO>
