</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: Current Trends in Reform Proposals -- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>
<br>
<h3>CURRENT TRENDS IN REFORM PROPOSALS</h3>
Almost everyone in the device industry now
supports regulatory reform of one sort or another and agrees that
many areas of industry are severely constrained by excessive governmental
mandates<sup><a href="foot.html">18</a></sup>. There is widespread recognition that regulatory bodies
impose large costs in terms of increased prices and loss of desirable
employment opportunities as well as decreased opportunities for
innovation. In the medical device field, many organizations have
proposed relief from particularly burdensome regulations, often
without first seriously considering the possibility of fundamental
reform. In general, trade organizations, which primarily represent
large manufacturers, tend to shy away from fundamental reform,
while representatives of the smaller manufacturers tend to be
more willing to consider basic issues. This to be expected. Large
companies can better afford the large expensive specialized staff
needed to deal with the FDA. Furthermore, in the device industry,
small companies tend to be responsible for a disproportionate
share of significant innovation and thus are most constrained
by excessive and inappropriate regulation. Finally, burdensome
regulations may, in the short run, work to the benefit of established
firms because they make it more difficult for new, and often smaller,
manufacturers to enter the market. There are, of course, many
exceptions to these generalizations.<BR>

<P>
Current popular proposals for regulatory reform
can be conveniently divided into three categories. One group of
reform proposals is directed at ensuring that the FDA acts  expeditiously.
A second seeks to break the FDA's monopoly. Finally, there is
a host of proposals narrowly aimed at very specific regulatory
abuses.<BR>

<P>
<U>More Expeditious Review</U>
<P>
The 1976 law envisioned very rapid review of
new products. In fact it can be argued that, except for the minority
of devices in FDA Class 3, there was no <I>requirement</I> for
premarket review at all. Only notification of the intention to
market was required. In fact, over the years, there have been
attempts to obfuscate the fact that the FDA has tolerated very
long review cycles. Thus, the FDA at times has reported median
review times, effectively disregarding cases where the delays
have been very long indeed; has not counted the time taken by
manufactures to respond to sometimes inappropriate FDA questions
and requests; and, has pressured manufactures to &quot;request&quot;
that the FDA &quot;stop the clock.&quot; The delays involve much
more than new product applications and include, for example, the
entire process for appropriately reclassifying totally new products
after they have been initially placed arbitrarily in Class 3.
The problem facing reformers who attempt to address the issue
of excessive delays is what to do if, as in the past, the FDA
simply does not comply with the legally established deadlines.
One suggested approach is to not require FDA notification for
less complex devices, perhaps all of Class 1 devices and certain
designated types of Class 2 devices. Such self-certifying is very
close to analogous features in the European Union system. However,
this begs the question of responsibility for the classification
itself. In the FDA system, devices are classified in Class 1 if
&quot;general controls&quot; are sufficient to ensure safety.
Such a criterion is at best subjective and contrasts markedly
with the rather explicit and objective European system. Allowing
manufacturers to self certify Class 1 devices, without reforming
the classification system itself, might break down in practice
into endless litigation.<BR>

<P>
A second difficult issue is what to do if a
manufacturer in good faith places a device in Class 1, manufactures
and markets it and later the FDA decides that the device needs
to adhere to &quot;performance standards&quot; and thus should
have been placed in Class 2. Certainly one would not want to force
such a device off the market if there were no reason to believe
that there were an actual safety problem. Again, the fundamental
need is unambiguous up-front classification.<BR>

<P>
Finally, there have been proposals to allow
marketing of devices which have been approved by the European
Union if FDA regulatory delays exceed statutory limits. It should
be noted that many U.S. products are or will be approved for marketing
in Europe. Such a proposal is an implicit recognition of the quality
of the European system, and one might question why one should
not simply recognize European certification and allow the FDA
and the European Union to engage in jurisdictional competition.
One could also envision that a system which recognized European
approvals only after the FDA failed to act expeditiously might
well exacerbate the adversarial nature of the approval system.
<BR>

<P>
Eventual approval is not sufficient to attract
venture capital needed to develop new products if the approval
process itself is subject to capricious delays due to regulatory
uncertainty. Harmonization of American and European standards,
so that there is an objective basis for mutual recognition, is
a far better answer<sup><a href="foot.html">19</a></sup>.<BR>

<P>
<U>The FDA Monopoly</U>
<P>
A number of current proposals seek to break
the FDA monopoly by privatizing some FDA functions. The inspiration
is clearly from the European Union system where <I>competing</I>
private &quot;notified bodies&quot; certify that the manufacturer
has met the explicit requirements which justify the manufacturer
applying a CE mark (of approval) to it products. Unfortunately,
many current proposals fail to recognize that the virtue of the
European system lies in the fact that the European notified bodies
are expected to exercise independent judgement and are not merely
arms of the central governmental authority. Furthermore, to the
extent possible, their evaluations and decisions are based on
detailed published international standards. Contracting out current
FDA functions to private bodies without first rationalizing these
functions simply substitutes different organizations and different
workers. While there may be some virtue using an organization
that works more efficiently than many governmental agencies, the
more basic problem is with the process itself. Those proposals
which do not foster competition between private certifying bodies
by allowing manufacturers to choose the organization from which
to purchase certifying services would appear to offer limited
advantages.<BR>

<P>
<U>Specific Regulatory Abuses</U>
<P>
Finally, there is a whole series of miscellaneous
proposals that address specific abuses and problem areas. Some
seek to streamline programs that just do not work. This includes
the simplification of the device malfunction (vigilance) program
and the device tracking program. Others seek to eliminate programs
for which there is no logical rationale. This would include the
freeing of exports to first world countries which are perfectly
able to police their own markets. Others attack very narrow issues
which, for lack of a better term, can be classified as corrections
of abuse of power and dereliction of duty. These include attempts
to improve accountability by specifying which particular officials
can make certain decisions, mandating periodic meetings at the
manufacturer's request, requiring unequivocal classification of
a product as either a drug or a device, prohibiting the FDA from
making decisions based on cost-effectiveness, limiting the authority
of the FDA to require controlled clinical studies, prohibiting
the withholding of a classification decision based on GMP violations
and many other such important but narrow issues. While it might
be desirable to achieve immediate relief by instituting some of
these reforms, they represent an attempt to micromanage the FDA.
Without fundamental reform, they, like most well meaning efforts
at micromanagement, run the risk of exchanging of one set of problems
for another. In general, the reform effort would be better spent
seeking to change the system by going back to basic principles,
determining what is actually needed to protect patients, and devising
the most direct way of achieving this goal.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
