HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Sunday, 09-Feb-97 03:06:08 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 11-Jul-96 19:36:11 GMT
Content-length: 16029
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: Torts and the Current Regulations -- PFF </TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>
<h3>The Current Regulatory Structure
and Its Implications for Tort Liability</h3>
<P>
The current role of the government with respect
to pharmaceuticals and medical devices is twofold.  First, the
government reviews these products to ensure their safety and efficacy.
 Second, the government plays an informational role in establishing
the kinds of information that can be conveyed with respect to
the characteristics of these products and the associated risks.
 The discussion below will consider the role of regulatory compliance
defense with respect to each of these aspects of government regulation.
<BR>
<P>
<b>Pre-Market Approval of Pharmaceuticals<BR>
</b>

<P>
The first phase of government regulation of
the products is a determination of which pharmaceutical products
are permitted to be marketed.  The first stage of this process
typically involves the submission of an investigational new drug
application to conduct trials for a new drug.  The legal requirements
for this application require that the company provide information
with respect to the chemistry, pharmacology, toxicology, and results
of animal and laboratory testing.<sup><a href="foot.html">5</a></sup>  These trials may then begin
provided the FDA does not either request more information or modify
the protocol submitted by the company for the proposed clinical
trials.  From a practical standpoint, the nature of the protocols
are often dictated by the FDA.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
The clinical trial process consists of three
phases.  Phase one trials are designed to elicit information about
&quot;the metabolism and pharmacologic actions of the drugs in
humans, [and] the side effects associated with increasing doses.&quot;<sup><a href="foot.html">6</a></sup>
These tests are also intended to provide information pertaining
to the product's safety.  These phase one trials typically involve
tests on a small number of healthy adults- approximately 20-80
people.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
If the phase one trials are successful, the
company proceeds to undertake phase two trials, which typically
involve testing the drug on 200-300 people who have the specific
disease or condition for which the product is targeted.  The phase
two trials are &quot;conducted to evaluate the effectiveness of
the drug for a particular indication or indications in patients
with the disease or condition under study.&quot;<sup><a href="foot.html">7</a></sup>  In addition,
these trials are intended to assess whether there are adverse
side effects associated with the drug.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
If the phase two trials are also successful,
the company proceeds to the phase three clinical trials involving
1,000 - 3,000 patients who also have the specific condition or
disease for which the drug is targeted.<sup><a href="foot.html">8</a></sup>  As the phase three trials
reach conclusion, the company submits a new drug application (NDA)
to the FDA to obtain permission to sell the pharmaceutical product.
 This application must include both safety and efficacy information,
and it is a compendium of all the available data obtained thus
far regarding the performance of the drugs with respect to these
two objectives.  In addition, the NDA must include information
pertaining to the proposed labeling for the new drug.<sup><a href="foot.html">9</a></sup><BR>
</FONT>
<P>
In evaluating the NDA, the FDA must ensure
that the product complies with the Federal Food, Drug and Cosmetic
Act (FDCA) requirements pertaining to safety, and that &quot;substantial
evidence&quot; of efficacy be demonstrated.  This stage of the
drug approval process is often quite lengthy, as the FDA review
often takes years after the submission of the NDA.  In many cases
these delays arise because the FDA requests new information from
the pharmaceutical company.  Overall, the NDA process takes between
five to seven years and involves a cost that has been estimated
to be as high as $231 million for each NDA.<sup><a href="foot.html">10</a></sup><BR>
</FONT>
<P>
An additional cost of the drug lag is that
patients in the United States will be deprived of drugs that potentially
could reduce mortality and morbidity.  There are thus two types
of competing errors known as Type I and Type II errors that could
arise with respect to the approval of new drugs.  The FDA might
approve drugs that turn out to have adverse consequences such
as thalidomide, which was approved in Great Britain but never
approved for use in the United States.  On the other hand, the
FDA could fail to approve drugs that are beneficial and would
have reduced risks because of excessively stringent safety standards.
 Many academic critics of the FDA have charged that the FDA has
erred too greatly on the side of preventing errors of commission
rather than being concerned with the risks that would be averted
by the new drugs that it fails to approve.<sup><a href="foot.html">11</a></sup>  The AIDS lobbyists
have called particular attention to the effect of these substantial
delays as well as the imbalance in attention that the FDA places
on errors of commission as opposed to errors of omission.  This
special disease interest lobbying group has succeeded in expediting
the review process for AIDS-related drugs.  Other potential beneficiaries
of drugs that are delayed by the lengthy review process are not
as well organized and are not as effective in bringing political
pressure to bear to make the FDA more responsive to the patients
who could benefit from these new products.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
The primary implication of this stringent drug
approval process for the regulatory compliance defense is that
the current concern with the potential safety of new drugs is
already quite substantial.  Indeed, from an economic efficiency
standpoint, one might well argue that the FDA places excessive
reliance on safety, particularly on the safety aspects pertaining
to adverse effects that might be created by drugs.  All that is
needed for purposes of the subsequent discussion of the regulatory
compliance defense is the general result that the FDA procedures
or privately operated procedures will ensure adequate levels of
safety.  These tests will fulfill a company's obligation to provide
an efficient level of safety associated with its products. <BR>
<P>
<b>Regulation of Drug Labeling<BR>
</b>

<P>
Prescription drugs by their very nature pose
potential risks either from misuse or adverse reactions, which
leads to the prescription requirement.  Medical devices also pose
potential risks of a similar nature.  As a result, the FDA requires
that information pertaining to the associated risks be provided
with these products.  In the case of pharmaceutical products,
the warning label must communicate both the overall risk associated
with the product as well as any specific risks associated with
particular groups of product users.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
Under the regulatory system established by
the FDCA, the FDA is largely responsible for writing the complete
content of the package inserts<sup><a href="foot.html">12</a></sup> that accompany pharmaceutical products.
 One former FDA General Counsel observed that the &quot;FDA ...
retains, as a practical matter, complete control over package
inserts.&quot;  Unlike the warnings practices under the OSHA hazard
communications standard or EPA labeling requirements for pesticides,
the FDA has both substantial control of the content of the warnings
as well as the warning structure.  In particular, the FDA has
in place a standardized warnings vocabulary that is used to communicate
the risks associated with the drugs.  This vocabulary stipulates
which kinds of information are presented in different places on
the label as well as how different variations in the label, such
as boxing of warnings or larger print, should be used to highlight
specific warnings.  Because of the standardized warnings approach
and the fact that physicians receive training in the processing
of such warning information in pharmacology courses, this system
provides an efficient means of communicating risk information
to the learned intermediary involved in prescribing pharmaceutical
products.  The fact that it is not the patient, but rather the
physician (learned intermediary) who is the target audience for
the warnings greatly affects the character and content of the
warnings message.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
The FDA does not develop the warnings language
in isolation.  Rather, the manufacturer is required to submit
to the FDA information pertaining to both the safety and the efficacy
of the product as part of its NDA.  In addition, the manufacturer
must submit proposed labeling for the drug for the FDA review.<sup><a href="foot.html">13</a></sup>
 In conjunction with the manufacturer, the FDA develops the initial
label for the drug.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
There is often a bargaining process between
the FDA and the manufacturer over the content of the warning label.
 The FDA has the ultimate authority since approval of the labeling
is a necessary part of the NDA approval process.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
The structure of the warnings vocabulary developed
by the FDA consists of the following sections.  The first section
of the warning label provides information that describes the general
characteristics of the product.<sup><a href="foot.html">14</a></sup>  The second section of the warning
label consists of information pertaining to the clinical pharmacology
of the product, whereby the warning provides information pertaining
to how the particular product operates.  The third section of
the label provides information pertaining to the indications and
the usage of the drug, and this is followed by a contraindications
section indicating the situations under which the drug should
not be administered because of the particular risks that may be
involved.  This section is followed by a warnings section that
details the risks that arise both generally as well as in specific
situations with respect to the drug.  Less frequently occurring
risks are the subject of the precautions section.  Isolated and
more random reactions to the drug are the subject of the adverse
reactions section.  Following this series of risk information
sections, the warning concludes with information about the appropriate
dosage and administration of the product.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
The standardized structure of this warnings
vocabulary greatly facilitates the ability of the physician to
process the warnings information.  The FDA also ensures a uniformity
in the use of the warnings language and a correspondence between
the language and the severity of the particular outcomes being
characterized.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
This kind of standardization could be generalized
to contexts in which the FDA did not have the authority to control
and review warnings but instead established as a reference point
a warnings vocabulary framework.  Thus, companies could provide
information with respect to a drug following these guidelines
for the positioning of information and guidelines with respect
to the usage of labeling variations such as boxing of particular
warning sections.  Liability for the company could then be based
on whether the company adhered to the particular warnings vocabulary
guidelines given the characteristics of the product.  Thus, in
our subsequent discussion of the regulatory compliance defense,
no distinction will be made between a warnings policy mandated
by the FDA or a warnings policy based on guidelines established
by the FDA.  It must, however, by recognized that there may be
an additional liability exposure if the FDA does not operate and
specifically approve the warning since then the company must show
that this warning did in fact adhere to the regulatory guidelines.
<BR>
<P>
<b>Post-Marketing Information<BR>
</b>

<P>
After a drug is made available for sale, there
may be adverse consequences that are observed that were not apparent
during the testing process.  If these problems are particularly
severe, it may be appropriate to withdraw the drug from the market.
 Thus, the safety of the drug should be a continuing concern.
 Similarly, if there are adverse consequences associated with
the drug that were not included in the initial labeling, the hazard
information provided should be amended over time to reflect this
changing informational state.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
In each case the appropriate reference point
for whether a firm has met its obligation should be the state
of the information at that particular time.  Moreover, because
adverse reactions and effects of drugs are often the subject of
speculation involving small samples, there must be some test of
the scientific validity of the adverse information before companies
should be held responsible for incorporating it in the drug evaluation
process.  A patient administered a drug for a particular ailment
may experience some adverse health effect.  However, in the absence
of a controlled experiment, it is not possible to ascertain whether
this effect is a consequence of the drug or a random variation
in health status that would have occurred if the drug had not
been administered.  The medical literature is replete with possible
adverse effects of this kind.  Some of these are subsequently
bolstered by scientific data, and others prove to be aberrations
that are never established in the literature.  In retrospect,
it is often possible to point to instances in which there was
initial fragmentary evidence regarding an adverse effect that
is ultimately established, but what is important is whether the
information available at any particular point in time is sufficient
to provide a reason for concern.  Effects that appear clearcut
in hindsight may not be evident given the state of information
at an earlier time.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
In that regard, the FDCA requires that the
pharmaceutical companies share with the FDA information pertaining
to the post-marketing performance of the drug.  This surveillance
process requires that the company report adverse experiences associated
with the drug as well as epidemiologic studies.  The current requirements
are that a company must report any serious reactions to a drug
to the FDA within 15 working days of the receipt of the information.<sup><a href="foot.html">15</a></sup>
 The sources of information that the manufacturer must examine
for these post-marketing studies include clinical, epidemiological,
or surveillance studies, as well as information that appears in
the medical literature.  The FDA then uses that information to
assess whether the drug should continue to be marketed or whether
there should be some change in the labeling for it.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
These provisions ensure the safety of drugs
and the appropriateness of information provision.  Regulation
is consequently an ongoing process that continues to reflect the
evolving state of information with respect to the drug.  Under
the current procedures, the FDA must approve any post-marketing
changes associated with the labeling of the drug, although a company
is free to withdraw a drug from the market should it choose to
do so.<sup><a href="foot.html">16</a></sup>  However, if the company does take such unilateral action,
it must simultaneously seek FDA approval for it, and if the FDA
does not approve the change it can institute a regulatory action
against the company.  Moreover, the FDA can overrule the company's
decision to change the warning label if it believes that such
a change would be inappropriate.  <BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
