</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: Torts (Conclusion) -- PFF </TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>
<br>
<h3>CONCLUSION</h3>

<P>
<FONT >The pharmaceutical and medical device industry
is in many respects an anomaly with respect to its legal status.
 This industry has been the target of some of the most pathbreaking
and costly product liability suits.  Indeed, not only is the liability
burden for the pharmaceutical and medical device industry quite
high, it is extremely disproportionate to its sales when compared
to other manufacturing industries.  By almost any objective standard,
the pharmaceutical industry is an outlier in terms of the extent
to which it has been hard hit by the rise in liability costs.
 These liability costs have been of substantial practical consequence,
as they have served as a deterrent to innovation and have discouraged
entry into important areas of product development.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >What is perhaps most disturbing about these
high liability costs is that they have been coupled with a regulatory
regime that is extremely stringent, certainly more stringent than
what is in place for any other major class of consumer products.
 Pharmaceutical products are subjected to extensive pre-market
testing and even extensive review before they are permitted to
be tested.  After having been tested and shown to be both safe
and effective, pharmaceutical products are marketed under restricted
market conditions in which a physician must prescribe prescription
drugs before they can be purchased.  In addition, the product
is accompanied by an on-product warning or a patient package insert,
the wording of which is specifically approved by the Food and
Drug Administration and is in large part drafted by the Food and
Drug Administration to be in conformance with a standardized warnings
vocabulary.  After the products are on the market, the Food and
Drug Administration undertakes considerable effort with respect
to surveillance of products and monitoring of adverse effects
that are reported to it.  This extremely vigorous regulatory regime
ensures that the usual tort liability objective of striking an
appropriate balance in the promotion of safety for the product
has been achieved.  Indeed, most critics of the FDA suggest that
the FDA errs on the side of excessive caution leading to too few
innovative new drugs reaching the market.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >In the presence of such stringent regulatory
criteria, one wonders why the pharmaceutical industry has been
the object of such extensive litigation.  The reason is not that
the FDA's judgements were in error.  Rather, in some cases new
information becomes apparent over time, which could not have been
known by either the company or by the FDA without even a more
extensive testing process that would have delayed potentially
beneficial drugs from reaching the market even longer.  More important
is that in a regime of strict liability the company will assume
responsibility for insuring any adverse outcomes that occur in
any patient population group.  In some cases there may be adverse
reactions to a drug that lead to a patient injury and a subsequent
lawsuit.  In other instances, the causality may be difficult to
ascertain.  Pharmaceutical companies with their relatively deep
pockets may be held accountable for the losses even though their
product did not in fact cause the injury.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The liability regime we propose would remedy
the inequities created by a liability system that currently imposes
stringent penalties on an industry that already is subject to
extensive regulatory requirements.  A strong regulatory compliance
defense would recognize the role that FDA standards play in addressing
the product safety issue.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Other legal issues are also created by a broader
reform effort.  Under the proposed regulatory process for pharmaceuticals
and medical devices outlined here, DCBs would be potentially subject
to suits from both companies purchasing their services as well
as injured plaintiffs.  Suits on the part of companies that are
attempting to hold the DCBs to their contractual obligations are
entirely appropriate and should be permitted.  In addition, suits
against the DCBs on the basis of negligence in carrying our their
review functions also are appropriate.  At present, certifiers
such as Underwriters' Laboratory are not typically subject to
strict liability.  Nevertheless, it is appropriate to give DCBs
a formal exemption from strict liability in order to eliminate
the low probability chance of a high loss event that may lead
to the insolvency of the DCB.  The prospect of such suits would
deter entry into the DCB arena, which would not be a desirable
outcome.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The legal proposals accompanying our plan simply
involve recognition of the need for a regulatory compliance defense
and codifying the existing legal regime to provide a degree of
assurance that the current legal landscape will not be altered
in a way that will affect DCBs adversely.  Given the past performance
of the liability system, such as the imposition of retroactive
liability in the asbestos cases, the need for a safe harbor for
DCBs even on a limited basis may be desirable in reducing unreasonable
exposures to liability.  The overall objective of legal sanctions
is to maintain the incentives for efficient behavior on the part
of DCBs, and this can be done by adopting the legal reforms that
we have proposed.</FONT>
<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
