<sup><li></sup>SEC Report at 11.
<sup><li></sup>SEC Report at 32-34.
<sup><li></sup>For example according to the survey in Edison Electric Institute, August 1994, <i>State Regulation of Utility Diversification</i>, 37 Public Utility Commissions in all states and District of Columbia have authority over forming a holding company, and 30 of them have authority over setting up a subsidiary.
<sup><li></sup>National Association of Regulatory Utility Commissioners, <i>Utility Regulation Policy in the United States and Canada,</i> 1993-1994, at 24-25.
<sup><li></sup>SEC Report, Appendix A.
<sup><li></sup>Edison Electric Institute, August 1994, <i>State Regulation of Utility Diversification.</i>
<sup><li></sup>Baumol and Willig at 9.
<sup><li></sup>SEC Report.
<sup><li></sup>There are, however, questions about the effects of SEC orders on the ability of the FERC and state regulators to exercise their authority. See e.g. Ohio Power Co. V. FERC, 954 F. 2nd 779 (D.C. Cir.), cert. denied, 113 S. Ct. 483 (1992). However, many in Congress have expressed a willingness to remedy this effect. Indeed, the Telecommunications Act of 1996 included a provision nullifying the effect of the Ohio Power case for purposes of reviewing the reasonableness of a public utility seeking to recover in rates the cost of purchasing certain telecommunications services.
<sup><li></sup>SEC Report, Appendix A.
<sup><li></sup>States almost universally allow their PUC's to investigate the details of a utility's transactions with its affiliates. See Edison Electric Institute, <i>State Regulation of Utility Diversification</i>.
<sup><li></sup>SEC Report at 12-16 and 26-28.
<sup><li></sup>Baumol and Willig at 5.
<sup><li></sup>Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, <i>1995 Annual Report</i> at 18.
<sup><li></sup>Federal Power Act section 301(c), 16 U.S.C. 825(c). Chair Moler has, however, testified that the FERC would need additional statutory authority in this regard if PUHCA were repealed. 1995 Hearings before the House Subcommittees on Energy and Power, and Telecommunications and Finance.
<sup><li></sup>See National Association of Regulatory Utility Commissioners, <i>Utility Regulatory Policy in the United States and Canada, Compilation 1993-1994</i> (August 15, 1994).
<sup><li></sup>SEC Report at 140-141.
<sup><li></sup>Harvard study at 11.
<sup><li></sup>Supra.
<sup><li></sup>Baumol and Willig at 7.
<sup><li></sup>See Statement of the <i>U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission Concerning Proposals to Amend or Repeal the Public Utility Holding Act of 1935</i> (June 2, 1982).
<sup><li></sup>These are defined in section 2 of the Act.  SEC Report at 8.
<sup><li></sup>While the first exemption (Section 3(a)(2)) requires some explanation.  In order to meet the "predominantly a utility exemption" three conditions must be met: the parent is predominantly a utility, the operations of the holding company system are limited to the state in which the parent is organized and contiguous states, and the parent is three to four times the size of its utility subsidiaries in terms of total revenues.
<sup><li></sup>P.L.  101-572.

</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center>
