<HEAD>
<TITLE>Higgins</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="discussi.gif">
<hr>
<blockquote>
<font face="arial">
<h2>HEATHER R. HIGGINS</h2>
<img src="higgins.gif" align=left>
Mrs. Higgins is the Executive Director of the Council on Culture & Community, an organization whose purpose concerns the examination and promotion of those attitudes and values necessary to democratic capitalism and American civilization, and a Senior Fellow at the Progress & Freedom Foundation.<p>
Before moving to the non-profit sector, Mrs. Higgins worked on Wall Street for seven years, where most recently she served as a portfolio manager and Vice President at U.S. Trust. She has also been an editorial writer for <i>The Wall Street Journal</i> and an assistant editor at <i>The Public Interest</i>.<p>
Mrs. Higgins is a frequent political commentator, appearing on such shows as <i>CNN & Co., Crossfire, To the Contrary,</i> and <i>Politically Incorrect.</i> She cohosts, with Newt Gingrich, <i>The Progress Report</i>, a live weekly hour-long program on public policy issues. Additionally, she wrote an occasional guest column for <i>NY Newsday</i>.<p>
Mrs. Higgins serves as a Board Member of the W. H. Brady Foundation, The Hoover Institution, Smith Richardson Foundation, Independent Women's Forum and as an Advisory Board Member of the Donner Foundation's New Leadership Fellows Project. She is also 1st Vice President of the Women's National Republican Club, as well as serving as a member of House Speaker Newt Gingrich's Strategy Team.
<p>
A 1981 graduate of Wellesley College, with a B.A. in English, Mrs. Higgins holds an M.B.A. in Finance from New York University.<p>
Mrs. Higgins most recent articles include: "The Principle Behind the Policies" (<I>Wall Street Journal</I>, 2/16/95), "Bobbitt: A Verdict that Kills Justice" (<I>Wall Street Journal</I>, 1/24/94), "What Next?" (<I>National Review</I>, 2/15/93), "Whither the Kulturkampf?" (<i>Crisis</i>, 3/92), and "The Politics of Virtue" (<I>Policy Review</I>, Fall, 1991). She is a contributing author to <i>Building a Community of Citizens: Civil Society in the 21st Century.  The Quotable Paul Johnson,</i> which she edited with George Marlin and Richard Rabatin, was published by Farrar, Straus & Giroux in Nov., 1994.
</font>
