<html>
<head>
<title>Biography:</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<img src="discussi.gif">
<hr>
<blockquote>
<font face="arial">
<h2>George A. Keyworth, II</h2>

George A. Keyworth, II, Ph.D., is the chairman of The Progress &
Freedom Foundation's Board of Directors and serves the Foundation as a
Senior Fellow.

<p>
<img src="keyworth.gif" align=right hspace=10 vspace=10>
<p>

From May 19, 1981, to December 31, 1985, Dr. Keyworth served as
Science Advisor to President Reagan and concurrently, Director of the
White House Office of Science and Technology Policy.  As a senior
member of the President's staff, he played key roles in the
modernization of strategic military forces and in the Strategic
Defense Initiative.  Dr. Keyworth was also deeply involved in
Administration initiatives to better utilize science and technology to
support U.S. foreign policy interests, especially with the People's
Republic of China, India, Japan, and Europe.

<p>

Prior to his White House service, Dr. Keyworth was Director of the
Physics Division at Los Alamos National Laboratory which he joined in
1968, leading the laboratory's programs in experimental physics,
condensed matter research, astrophysics and space science and laser
fusion.

<p>

In 1986, Dr. Keyworth established The Keyworth Company, a
Washington-based firm committed to working with companies in
developing strategies for growth, and became a Senior Fellow and
Director of Research at the Hudson Institute.

<p>

Dr. Keyworth is a graduate of Yale University with a B.S. in physics.
He was awarded a Ph.D. in nuclear physics from Duke University in
1968, where he conducted pioneering research in isospin conservation
in nuclear reactions.

<p>

In addition to his involvement with the Foundation, Dr. Keyworth is a
Fellow of both the American Physical Society and the American
Association for the Advancement of Science.  He serves on the Board of
Directors of the Hewlett Packard Company, O'Neill Communications,
Inc., Signition, Inc., and the Santa Fe Institute.  He is also a
member of Phi Beta Kappa, the honorary scientific society Sigma Xi,
and a Governor of the National Space Club.  His honors include a
D.Sc. from Rennselaer Polytechnic Institute, A D. Eng. from Michigan
Technological University and D. Sc. from the University of Alabama.
He is also an Honorary Professor of Fudan University in Shanghai, the
People's Republic of China.  In 1987, he received the fourth Hertz
Foundation Award.  Currently, Dr. Keyworth serves as Chairman for the
Council on Superconductivity for American Competitiveness.

</font>
</body>
</html>

