<HEAD>
<TITLE> Welcome Aspen 1996 </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">
<blockquote>
<img src="/pff/bi.gif" align="left">
<p align="right">				August 4, 1996</p>
<p><br>
<h2><center>Welcome To Aspen 1996</h2></center>
<p>

Dear Aspen Summit '96 Participant:
<P>
Welcome!  We are glad you could join us in Aspen  a much more comfortable venue in August than Atlanta, where PFF held its first <i>Cyberspace and the American Dream</i> conference in 1994.
<P>
Since then, the Digital Revolution has kept up its frantic pace:  Java, Netscape, Windows 95, the Communications Decency Act, the debate over encryption and intellectual property, the Telecommunications Act of 1996, Pat Buchanan and the rise of the "New Luddites" -- all in three years.
<P>
It's hard keeping up, and even harder to keep it all in perspective.  During the next two days, we hope you'll learn something about what's happening and is about to happen as a result of the Digital Revolution.  But even more importantly, we hope this two-day "breather" will give you, and us, a chance to step back and gain some perspective on the promise and the peril of our times.
<P>
That, of course, is our main theme -- reminding ourselves that America's continued progress in the Digital Revolution is not something to take for granted.  From Al Toffler's opening speech, "Future Shock in the Present Tense," to our closing debate on whether "growth of the Internet is a 'Leading Cultural Indicator' of American progress," we want to remind ourselves that great civilizations sometimes choose paths leading to decay -- even, or perhaps especially, in a digital world.
<P>
A second theme of this year's conference is "theory vs. practice."  We are delighted at the number and quality of representatives attending this year from America's leading technology companies, and confident that their participation will 
ensure a healthy mix between the thinkers and theoreticians and the doers and practitioners.
<P>
The Progress & Freedom Foundation has grown up with the Digital Revolution.  It's in our blood, and because you are here, we know it's in yours too.  
<P><center>
Sincerely,
<P></center>
<pre>
	Jay Keyworth					Jeff Eisenach
	Chairman 					President
</pre>
<P>
P.S.  Next year's conference will be held here at the Ritz-Carlton Aspen in late July or early August.  As you can imagine, it's a popular spot, and we're booking early.  If  you would like to go ahead and pre-register for next year, please talk with Katherine Epler.
</blockquote>
<p><center>
[ <a href="http://www.pff.org/pff/aspen96/">Back to Aspen '96</a> ]
</font></center>

</BODY>
