<DOCHDR>
http://www.conservative.org:80/pff/clean/sect2.html 204.71.237.88 19970209113610 text/html 32494
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Sunday, 09-Feb-97 11:36:56 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 11-Jul-96 19:36:39 GMT
Content-length: 32308
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Section 2: Infrastructure Challenge</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717"
Vlink="545454" ALINK="#FF0000"><ul><blockquote>
 <a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif"
 align="right" border="0"></a>

<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">II. THE INFRASTRUCTURE CHALLENGE</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">BACKGROUND AND INSTITUTIONS</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Pressure for the development and introduction
of AFVs is driven by two goals.  One relates to efforts to reduce
the importation of oil especially from the Persian Gulf, discussed
more fully below.  The more binding goal relates to mobile-source
emissions, which is another way of saying emissions from autos,
trucks and buses.  Simply stated, many U.S. cities have not met
the National Ambient Air Quality Standards (NAAQS), first put
forward in the 1970 Clean Air Act and subsequently revised and
raised.<sup><a href="end.html">9</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The problem fundamentally relates to ozone,
which falls into two categories.<sup><a href="end.html">10</a></sup>
 The first is found in the upper
atmosphere; this is good ozone that protects the population from
intense sun rays that cause skin cancer.  There is also a lower
atmospheric or terrestrial ozone, which is produced by a complex
reaction of nitrogen oxides (NOx) and volatile organic compounds
(VOCs), like hydrocarbons, in the presence of sunlight.  It is
this lower atmospheric ozone that yields smog, which in turn causes
respiratory and other health problems as well as damage to agricultural
crops.<sup><a href="end.html">11</a></sup>  </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Ozone is produced each day, rising with the
amount of sunlight and falling to low levels at night.  There
is little if any sustained accumulation from one day to the next,
although ozone can travel as far as 100 miles from its source.
Heat and light being necessary for ozone reaction, the levels
produced follow seasonal patterns; the worst periods occurring
in the spring and summer. The amount of ozone produced results
from the production of the ozone-related emissions, atmospheric
conditions and natural background levels of VOCs.  Population
density, ozone concentration and ozone movement determine the
extent to which ozone production is a health problem. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The ozone creation problem is inherently local,
with wide differences across cities. Chilton and Boemer point
out: </FONT>
<P><blockquote>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Ozone's real-world chemistry is even more dynamic
than this, however - VOC-NOx ratios can change throughout a single
day.  Ratios also vary by metropolitan area and can differ within
portions of an individual city.  Further, the relative amounts
of VOCs and NOx in the air are linked to the location and size
of their sources and the movement of air masses.  VOCs originate
most from vehicle emissions, chemical and petroleum refining companies,
industrial solvents and natural vegetation.<sup><a href="end.html">12</a></sup>  </FONT>
</blockquote><P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Continuing with their discussion, Chilton and
Boemer indicate that trees and other vegetation are significant
sources of background VOCs, and, of course, urban vegetation varies
significantly across metropolitan areas.  Indeed, the National
Research Council (NRC) of the National Academy of Science estimates
that background levels of ozone are of &quot;comparable magnitude&quot;
to man-made VOC emissions and that complete elimination of man-made
sources could leave enough VOC sources to produce smog.
<sup><a href="end.html">13</a></sup>  Finally,
the NRC indicates that solutions to local ozone problems must
be custom-tailored to solve local problems.<sup><a href="end.html">14</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The variation in ozone levels and conditions
across cities can be seen in other ways.  Since passage of the
CAA, ozone levels have changed dramatically in a number of cities.
 Jones and Adler indicate that it &quot;is difficult to identify
a significant air pollution problem outside California.&quot;
<sup><a href="end.html">15</a></sup>
 From 1992 to 1994, the reduction in ozone above allowable levels
for the rest of the nation fell by 57 percent.  For California,
the reduction was 27 percent.  From 1988 to 1990, the years reflected
in the CAA mandate, the nonattainment regions totaled 85, with
40 marginal.  Using 1992-94 data, the total was 18 with 12 marginal.
<sup><a href="end.html">16</a></sup>
 Even so, the 1988-90 data continue to define the problem, and
the various control regions, even those that are cleaner, must
follow the CAA prescription.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">The 1990 Clean Air Act Amendments:
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">A Decentralized Approach to the
Problem</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The 1990 Clean Air Amendments (CAA) defined
the nonattainment problem based on 1988-1990 emissions data. 
By that measure, some 96 urban areas were designated to be in
ozone nonattainment categories that ranged from moderate to serious,
severe and extreme.<sup><a href="end.html">17</a></sup>  
Excluding the moderate category leaves 22
cities (shown in Figure 1) with the most difficult statute-based
ozone standards to meet.  In addition, some 13 metropolitan areas
(including some of the 22 above) exceeded NAAQS for carbon monoxide,
again using 1988-1990 data.<BR>
</FONT>
<HR>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="usmap.gif" align =right></CENTER>
<FONT FACE="Arial">CA</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">CO</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">CT</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">GA</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">LA</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">MA</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">MD</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">PA</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">TX</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">VA</FONT>
<p>
<hr>
<FONT FACE="Arial">To address the nonattainment and other vehicle
emissions problems, the CAA set tighter emission standards for
the national auto fleet, to be fully achieved by the 1996 model
year.<sup><a href="end.html">18</a></sup> 
The standard for exhaust emissions of hydrocarbons was
cut from the previous standard of 0.41 grams per mile (gpm) to
0.25 gpm and the standard for nitrogen oxides, from 1.0 gpm to
0.4 gpm.  Emission limits for carbon monoxide remained at 3.4
gpm.<sup><a href="end.html">19</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Breaking with the national scheme, the statute
set stricter hydrocarbon emission standards for a California pilot
program (0.125 gpm) - in effect establishing two standards to
be met by auto producers.<sup><a href="end.html">20</a></sup>
  Along with defining specific metropolitan
and California attainment challenges, the statute took one more
step toward decentralized control by establishing a northeastern
state ozone control region required to reach beyond the national
baseline standards.  In addition, the 1990 law ordered auto firms
to provide cleaner, if not zero, emission automobiles, and mandated
the sale of reformulated, cleaner-burning gasoline.  The CAA also
addressed truck and other vehicle emissions and required EPA to
focus on emissions from boats, farm equipment, lawn mowers, and
construction machinery.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">While forcing attention on alternative fuels,
but not requiring their use, the 1990 CAA ordered cleaner-burning
gasoline to be marketed in cities that failed to meet NAAQS for

carbon monoxide (CO) and ozone.<sup><a href="end.html">21</a></sup>
   Starting in 1992, 39 nonattainment
areas were required, during part of the year, to use oxygenated
fuels, that blend oxygenated compounds with gasoline.  The intent
here was to reduce hydrocarbon and CO emissions which are a weaker
but still significant smog precursors.<sup><a href="end.html">22</a></sup>
  Reformulated (cleaner-burning)
gasoline, a distinct gasoline product not to be confused with
oxygenated gasoline, adds yet one more dimension to the clean
air arsenal. Mandated for the country's nine worst ozone areas
starting in 1995, a two-phase program calls for a 15 percent reduction
in volatile organic compounds beginning in 1995, and a 25 percent
reduction beginning in 2000.<sup><a href="end.html">23</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Under the CAA, ozone nonattainment areas are
to develop state implementation plans (SIPs) to achieve 15 percent
ozone reductions in areas classified as moderate, serious, severe
and extreme ozone  nonattainment areas.  The statute requires
a Clean Fuel Fleet program for operators of 10 or more centrally
refueled vehicles in these areas.<sup><a href="end.html">24</a></sup>
  However, the law does not mandate
the use of any particular fuel but simply requires that California
emission standards be met.<sup><a href="end.html">25</a></sup>
  Beginning in 1996, the nonattainment
areas are required to show an additional three percent reduction
each year until the attainment goal is achieved.  Failure to accomplish
these goals can lead to losses of federal transportation funds
and stiff emissions offset requirements from existing polluters
when new stationary sources seek approval.<sup><a href="end.html">26</a></sup>
  </FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">The Ozone Transport Region</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Air pollution is not a national problem in
the sense that a well-specified set of pollutants is uniformly
affecting every citizen across all 50 states.  Air pollution is
a decidedly local and regional problem.  Recognizing this, the
CAA sets national baseline standards that must be achieved throughout
the nation, but then sets different standards for California,
22 urban areas, and 12 northeastern states.  Reaching from northern
Virginia, including the District of Columbia, and extending to
Maine, these 12 states form the Ozone Transport Region.
<sup><a href="end.html">27</a></sup>  Cooperation
across part of this region developed in 1967, when nine of the
12 states formed the Northeast States for Coordinated Air Use
Management, which continues to operate.<sup>
<a href="end.html">28</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The CAA effectively establishes for the 12-state
region an environmental cartel managed by the Ozone Transport
Commission.  The Commission consists of state governors, the EPA
Administrator, EPA regional administrators, and state air pollution
control officers.  Like all cartels, gaining agreement among diverse
groups is not always easy.  The Commission is charged with the
difficult task of determining a <I>uniform</I> strategy for dealing
with ozone pollution in the 12-state region.  By statute, the
Commission may select to meet its goals by adopting California
standards and California vehicles or by adopting some other clean
fuel strategy - but the Commission may not settle on a technology
that requires the auto industry to produce a third vehicle type
for the U.S. market.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In 1994, the Commission attempted to require
the use of California low emission vehicles (LEVs) as a major
component of its ozone reduction scheme.  The LEVs would have
been electric vehicles.  However, no agreement could be reached
across the 12 states, and the U.S. auto industry filed suit in
those states that had already adopted the LEV rule, arguing that
an LEV for the northeast would be a third car.
<sup><a href="end.html">29</a>
</sup>  In brief, the
argument turned on the notion that because of differences in climate,
requiring colder starts and requirements for energy-using heaters,
a northeastern LEV would be different from a California LEV.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The industry is seeking to persuade the Commission
to adopt a cleaner-fuel approach and has committed itself to provide
a National Low Emission Vehicle (NLEVs) that would satisfy the
ozone reduction requirements of the Northeast Ozone Transport
Region.<sup><a href="end.html">30</a></sup>
  This salvo by the auto industry advanced the prospects
for some AFVs in the large northeastern market, but practically
eliminated the prospects for electric cars in that region.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">The Energy Policy Act of 1992</FONT></B></CENTER><P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Energy security, a motivating factor behind
the Energy Policy Act of 1992 (EPACT), is a second force pushing
for alternative fuel vehicles.<sup><a href="end.html">31</a></sup>
  EPACT, passed in the wake of the
1990-91 Gulf War, is a prime example of crisis-borne legislation.
 Since 1951, petroleum supply lines from the Gulf have been disrupted
13 times, with the largest supply shortfall occurring during the
Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in August-October 1990.
<sup><a href="end.html">32</a>
</sup>  In each case,
the U.S. economy was seriously affected.  After declaring an energy
crisis at hand the Congress responded by passing legislation that
sought to buffer the economy from future oil shocks.  The Gulf
region now provides about 50 percent of U.S.-consumed crude oil,
a share that is predicted to rise to 60 percent over the next
10 years.<sup><a href="end.html">33</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">As described by the U.S. Department of Energy
(DOE), EPACT &quot;was enacted to stimulate the research, development,
and accelerated introduction of technologies that can potentially
shift the focus of national energy demand away from imported oil
and toward renewable or domestically produced energy sources.&quot;
<sup><a href="end.html">34</a></sup>
 EPACT requires DOE to promote alternative fuels that reduce consumption
of gasoline and diesel fuel and to determine the feasibility of
meeting EPACT requirements of replacing 10 percent of all petroleum-based
motor fuels by the year 2000 and 30 percent by 2010.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Of course, EPACT was not born an orphan.  Its
legislative parents were the Alternative Motor Fuel Act of 1988
and the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990.  These were then strengthened
by executive orders issued in 1991 by President Bush and in 1993
by President Clinton.<sup><a href="end.html">35</a></sup>  Both executive orders accelerated the purchase
of alternative fuel vehicles for the federal government's vehicle
fleet.  President Clinton's order called for 1993, 1994 and 1995
purchases of 7,500, 11,250 and 15,000 AFVs, respectively.
<sup><a href="end.html">36</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The definition of alternative fuels turns on
the effort to reduce reliance on imported petroleum products.
 These include methanol, ethanol, mixtures containing 85 percent
or more by volume of alcohols with gasoline, natural gas, liquefied
petroleum gas, hydrogen, coal-derived fuels, electricity and anything
else that is clearly not petroleum.  Reformulated gasoline and
innovative fuels such as mixtures of water and petroleum-based
naptha, that may be cleaner than the fuels just mentioned, do
not receive EPACT's blessing.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">EPACT's goals for replacing gasoline are ambitious
but currently unattainable.<sup><a href="end.html">37</a>
</sup>  In 1993, the total number of vehicles
that were part of a public or private fleet, was approximately
13.5 million - less than 10 percent of the 190 million vehicles
on the road. Among the 13.5 million fleet vehicles, only 550,000
were in the federal fleet, where EPACT has the greatest leverage.
 Thus to accomplish EPACT's goal, the private fleet must be affected
more significantly.  In 1994, DOE estimated that all of EPACT's
efforts would lead to a reduction of 400,000 barrels of gasoline
per day consumed in the year 2010, about five percent of the total
but nowhere near the 30 percent targeted by EPACT.  Speaking to
the fundamental energy security goal and neglecting the definition
of alternative fuels, the U.S. General Accounting Office indicates
that eight percent of the total gasoline consumed can be reduced
through the use of nonpetroleum-based oxygenates in gasoline.
<sup><a href="end.html">38</a></sup>
 In addition, the 4.3 cents fuel tax added by the 1993 Omnibus
Budget Reconciliation Act raised the already high hurdles to be
jumped by producers of AFVs and fuels, since the uniform increase
across fuels yields a disproportionate increase in the price of
some alternative fuels.  For example, a 4.3 cents per gallon increase
for CNG, which sells at approximately 90 cents a gasoline equivalent
gallon, is a distinctly larger increase in price than 4.3 cents
on gasoline that sells for $1.15 gallon. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">CAFE Standards: A Companion to EPACT</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">EPACT's energy security goal is shared by the
1975 Energy Policy and Conservation Act, which established corporate
average fuel economy standards (CAFE) for the U.S. passenger car
fleet beginning in 1978.<sup><a href="end.html">39</a>
</sup>  By statute, firms providing vehicles
to the U.S. fleet must meet an average CAFE for their new car
fleets that accounts for the mix of models produced and sold in
a given year.  A firm that fails to achieve the standard is fined
$50 per mile per gallon per car produced.  Firms may earn credits
in years when they exceed the standard that can be applied to
penalty years.  The CAFE standard has been raised over the years
and is now set at 27.5 mpg for model years 1985 and beyond.  CAFE's
goal relates directly to reducing the importation of crude oil
and petroleum products. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">CAFE's history is controversial.  Auto producers
struggled to meet the rising standard.  For instance, at times
the declining relative price of gasoline made larger and heavier
cars more attractive to consumers; yet to meet CAFE standards,
the auto producers made smaller cars not wanted by dealers or
consumers.  CAFE also had the effect of encouraging foreign producers,
which typically provided smaller, more fuel efficient cars, to
increase the average size of the cars they sold in the United
States.  Thus while domestic producers reduced the sizes of their
standard vehicles, foreign producers scaled up, resulting in an
average vehicle sold in America that was smaller, lighter, and
therefore less crashworthy.  At the margin, fuel economy is substituted
for passenger safety.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The fatality effect of CAFE was estimated by
Crandall and Graham for the 1989 fleet.<sup><a href="end.html">40</a></sup>
  Their analysis shows
that CAFE is associated with 2,200 to 3,900 excess occupant fatalities
per year.  Crandall and Graham also estimated the number of excess
serious injuries triggered by the lighter cars derived from CAFE,
finding 11,000 to 19,500 additional serious injuries in 1989.
 If a value of $1 million is assigned to each life lost and $20,000
is assigned to each serious injury (the values used by Crandall
and Graham), CAFE's adverse safety cost carries a price tag of
approximately $1.9 to $3.4 billion over the life of a given model-year
car.  Put simply, the avoidance of imported oil carries a high
price.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Since EPACT and CAFE share the same goal, it
seems logical to consider the relative merits of substituting
AFVs for CAFE.  In fact, auto producers receive a credit against
their CAFE obligation for each AFV they produce and sell.  Instead
of raising CAFE to higher levels and generating more excess fatalities
and injuries, CAFE could be eliminated.  Efforts made by auto
producers to achieve the current CAFE or even higher future standards
could be diverted to the design and production of AFVs, which
have a safety record that is superior to that of the national
fleet.<sup><a href="end.html">41</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">The Infrastructure Problem</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Those charged with promoting AFVs recognized
immediately that any significant move to fuels other than gasoline
requires a new fuel distribution system.  DOE's program, like
that in the CAA, first focuses on fleet operators where centralized
refueling and maintenance is cheaper.  The program combines education,
voluntary commitments from alternative fuel suppliers to build
distribution facilities, and requirements for alternative fuel
providers and other federal and state fleet operators to expand
the number of AFVs.  The Department of Energy's March 27, 1996,
announcement of purchase requirements to be met by alternative
fuel providers spells out the fleet requirements.
<sup><a href="end.html">42</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Referring to EPACT, the rules mandate purchase
of AFVs by state and local governments, fuel providers, and related
petroleum and chemical companies.  Some 10 percent of newly purchased
light duty vehicles for the affected fleets must be AFVs for model
year 1997.  The share rises in subsequent years, reaching 75 percent
for model year 2001 and thereafter.  To encourage accelerated
progress toward the ultimate goal, the rules include a system
of tradable credits that arise when a purchaser goes beyond the
minimum number required in a given model year.  These credits
can be applied in subsequent years to fill out a purchase shortfall,
or they can be sold to another fleet owner who fails to meet requirements.
  The DOE AFV initiatives also include a Clean Cities program
that promotes greater use of clean-fuel buses, a push for tax
incentives, state grants, and strategic efforts to locate the
placement of mandated federal AFVs.<sup><a href="end.html">43</a></sup> 
 Close to 50 cities have joined
the Clean Cities effort.  DOE's overall goal is to expand the
nation's AFV fleet from 421,000 vehicles in 1995 to almost 2.5
million by 2010.  Funding for the DOE effort has expanded from
$7 million in FY 1993 to $30 million in FY 1995, but funding for
future budgets is in serious doubt.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Among alternative fuels, compressed natural
gas (CNG) and electricity are the most ubiquitous.  These two
energy sources are supplied to nearly every home, business and
industry throughout the country.  The electricity available at
a home or business is ready to be used for charging an automobile
battery.  However, the natural gas delivered to a home or business
is at a much lower pressure than required for fueling a vehicle.
An investment of $500,000 or more in a compressor and related
equipment is required before a filling station can become a full-service
natural gas dispenser.  A home compressor unit requires an investment
of $5,000.  Liquid petroleum gas (LPG) - commonly known as propane
- is also widely available, with many refueling facilities located
near commercial users.  However, LPG does not compare with the
wide potential distribution of CNG, since natural gas is piped
to homes, industries and commercial establishments throughout
the United States.  Ethanol, which is typically produced from
corn, can be produced practically anywhere in America, blended
with gasoline and distributed across large regions.  Finally,
methanol, which is generally produced from natural gas, can be
made widely available.  According to DOE, there were 4,587 AFV
refueling stations in the nation's metropolitan areas in 1995,
a substantial increase from 1,398 in 1992.
<sup><a href="end.html">44</a>
</sup>  Of these, CNG had
1,078 stations, with locations in all states except Alaska, Maine,
and Mississippi.  In 1996, Maine is the last remaining state without
a CNG station.  Liquefied petroleum gas was available in 3,385
locations, with refueling stations lacking only in the District
of Columbia.  Blends of methanol and ethanol had 88 and 36 stations
respectively, but could be supplied from practically any filling
station.  </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In a country with more than 200,000 filling
stations, 4,587 alternative fuel stations looks rather pale, but
every state now has at least some refueling capability; some major
cities have a score.<sup><a href="end.html">45</a>
</sup>  In November 1995, <I>USA Today</I> reported
that four additional compressed natural gas stations were opening
each week.<sup><a href="end.html">46</a>
</sup>  As might be expected, concentration by state is associated
with the relative abundance of the fuel type.  California shows
a relatively large number of compressed natural gas and liquefied
petroleum gas stations, as does Texas and other gas-producing
states.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">When assessing availability, it is important
to focus on the fleets being targeted.  In the early stages of
entry, AFVs must be concentrated in locations with refueling capability.
 In some cases, these will be for fleets of trucks and light vehicles
that operate exclusively in particular metropolitan areas or regions.
 In other cases, the fleets may be a city bus system or vehicles
that support a major airport operation.  As fleets grow, and as
demand increases, refueling will grow simultaneously.  However,
in the early stages of market development the chicken and the
egg puzzle will always plague the supporting industry.  </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Just how large is the U.S. alternative fuel
fleet and what are its future prospects?  At the time of a DOE
1996 survey, there were some 421,000 AFVs in the U.S. fleet.
<sup><a href="end.html">47</a></sup> 
The 279,000 vehicles fueled by LPG account for the lion's share
of the total. With 84,000 vehicles, CNG stands in second place,
and vehicles using ethanol and methanol rank third and fourth,
with approximately 32,000 and 22,000 vehicles respectively.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">According to DOE, the gains experienced by
each vehicle type since 1992 show LPG vehicles have experienced
only small growth.<sup><a href="end.html">48</a></sup>
  Both methanol- and CNG-powered vehicles show
substantial growth, with CNG showing the more dramatic year-over-year
increases since 1993. However, there are expectations for the
1996 sale of ethanol-fueled vehicles to rise significantly, largely
due to General Motors' offering a bi-fueled pickup truck.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The composition of the AFV fleet is dominated
by the private sector, which owns some 342,000 of the total.
<sup><a href="end.html">49</a></sup> 
Most of the AFVs in the private fleet, some 265,000 vehicles,
are LPG-fueled vehicles.  CNG, with 38,000 vehicles, stands in
second place.  In 1996, state and local governments operated 42,000
AFVs.  CNG, fueling some 22,000 of these, was the dominant fuel
type in that fleet.  Of the total, heavy duty vehicles such as
buses accounted for the major share. Even with purchases of AFVs
for the federal fleet stimulated by presidential executive orders,
the numbers in the federal fleet are still rather small. According
to DOE's 1996 survey, there are 36,571 AFVs in the federal fleet,
with CNG vehicles accounting for 23,744 of that number.  Nonetheless,
growth has been impressive; there were just 3,360 AFVs in the
federal fleet in 1992.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">According to DOE, the propane-fueled fleet
component is the oldest and is the least likely to expand markedly.
 The agency predicts CNG to be the growth component of the AFV
fleet, partly due to price and low emissions.  This is in spite
of the lack of refueling infrastructure and the challenges presented
by the requirement for larger on-board fuel tanks.
<sup><a href="end.html">50</a>
</sup>  The methanol/gasoline
blend AFVs are primarily in California, and many are urban buses.
 Government purchases of additional blended-fuel vehicles should
increase the number by 10,000 units in 1996.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">State Regulatory Hurdles</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Thus far, the entry of AFV technology has occurred
despite old-style public utility regulation that affects the pricing
and distribution of natural gas.  The identical problem would
face electricity providers if electric cars became a significant
competing technology.  The central issue relates to the regulation
of prices charged by local distribution companies, which are set
by state public utility commissions.  Traditionally viewed as
a monopolist, the natural gas distributor usually had an exclusive
area franchise in which it operated.  There was no direct competition
from other providers in the sale of the product to typical residential
and commercial customers, although large users could contract
with gas marketers and have their gas shipped from distant points.
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Public utility commissions engage in rate-of-return
regulation when setting prices.  Using a standard, but complicated,
approach, the regulatory body identifies an appropriate rate base,
determines what is to be included, and approves a pricing scheme
that yields some predicted rate of return to the gas distributor.
 Gas distributors and regulators engage in periodic struggles
when prices are to be altered.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The AFV market is different in significant
ways from the market for residential, commercial and industrial
gas.  Unlike the market for home-heating and industrial fuels,
CNG will compete head-to-head with gasoline and all other fuels
at the pump.  Of course, natural gas competes with electricity
in its monopoly market, but that competition ends when a customer
settles on a particular boiler or furnace technology. Competition
at the filling station is continuous, particularly for bi-fueled
vehicles, and the market turnover of automobiles occurs more frequently
than the turnover of home furnaces and industrial machinery.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The central problem here relates to incentives
for natural gas providers to assume a new market risk.  With traditional
rate regulation, there is no risk premium paid for the development
of a new market.  A conceptual solution to the problem lies in
separating the assets that serve the AFV market and allowing gas
providers complete freedom in setting price.  Alternately, gas
providers can be allowed to establish separate firms dedicated
to the AFV market.  These firms would buy natural gas from pipelines
or producers, paying the market price.  Then, they would sell
the gas to the AFV market at prices determined by market competition.
 Old-fashioned economic regulation applied traditionally to natural
gas providers will not work in the AFV market.  For the new technology
to enter, regulatory reform will be necessary.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Conclusion</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">There are distinct regional differences in
the ozone problem and differences in how people in various regions
are addressing the problem.  There are significant differences
in the availability of AFV fuels across regions as well as the
likely concentration of AFVs that could ultimately form viable
markets.<sup><a href="end.html">51</a></sup>  Given the differences in the air quality gap to be closed
and the regional options for closing it, logic suggests that the
instruments of control should be decentralized.  The success of
CAA and EPACT relies on actions to be taken by cities, states
and regions.  With NAAQS as a baseline, California standards higher
than the baseline, and with promises of cleaner fuel autos, logic
further suggests that city, state and regional control groups
should be given complete flexibility in determining incentive-based
rules for inducing technological change.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Yet this leaves a number of questions unanswered,
which will be addressed in following sections:  How can regions
that seek cleaner air make their desires known in the market place?
 After all, markets for air quality are few and far between. 
Should communities and regions consider modifying fuel taxes to
make cleaner-burning fuels more attractive?  Should subsidies
be provided to investors who build clean fuel filling stations?
 Or should consumers be given incentives to purchase cleaner cars
and fuels?  How would these incentives be calculated?  And where
might the zone of control be located?</FONT>
<p><br>
<a href="sect3.html">Next Section: Economic Incentives For The Production Of Cleaner Air</a><p>
<a href="sect1.html">Previous Section: Introduction</a><p>
<a href="end.html">End Notes</a>

</BODY>
</HTML>
