<html><head>
<title>Economic Incentives For The Production of Cleaner Air</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717"
Vlink="545454" ALINK="#FF0000"><ul><blockquote>
 <a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif"
 align="right" border="0"></a>

<B><FONT FACE="Arial">III.  ECONOMIC INCENTIVES FOR THE PRODUCTION
OF CLEANER AIR</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Air quality is a classic case of economic externalities
and the tragedy of the commons:  no one owns it, so no one wants
to pay to keep it clean.  Finding reliable incentives that encourage
people to treat air quality with owner-like concern is the crux
of the environmental challenge.  Air quality is a valuable asset,
but its price is zero.  People who want more clean air logically
feel more should be provided, without paying for it.  Those who
use air quality in manufacturing or in transportation tend to
think in terms of rules and regulation instead of having to confront
a monthly bill that accounts for their environmental use.  </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Were it not for transaction costs, solving
the problem would be simple.<sup><a href="end.html">52</a></sup>
  Property rights to defined elements
of the atmosphere could be placed in the hands of owners, be they
environmental organizations or private entrepreneurs.  These owners
would predictably recognize the value of alternative uses and
manage their asset to maximize its value.  Lovers of cleaner air
and people who wish to produce goods and services would compete
for use of the valuable rights.  In theory, the market process
would yield an effective and efficient outcome.  Taking another
theoretical approach, and assuming information and transaction
cost are negligible, wise politicians seeking to serve the public
interest could calculate taxes and fees to be imposed on individuals
who use the scarce atmosphere.<sup><a href="end.html">53</a></sup>
  Following this prescription, campers
who build fires and drivers of automobiles would receive bills
that reflect the cost they impose when consuming the environment.
 But, alas, the costs of such approaches are high.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Were it not for transaction costs, we could
rely on common law rules that endow environmental rights to all
property owners and offer protection when those rights are violated
against the owners' will.<sup><a href="end.html">54</a></sup>
  But while common law works well for
pollutants with a known, and readily controllable, source, the
rule of law faces severe challenges when the problem has to do
with millions of small emission sources that collectively produce
unwanted smog.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Assuming transaction costs are negligible,
we can imagine a community that sets a continually monitored baseline
for air quality.  The community could reward activities that improve
baseline conditions and penalize actions that tend to undermine
it.  The community could provide a scheme of subsidies and taxes
that affect the decisions of ordinary people, whether they be
environmentalists or not.  As explained more fully below, both
of these fiscal instruments are widely used in the United States.
 In recent years, countries across Europe have begun to base fuel
taxes on fuel emission characteristics.  For example, Germany,
Italy, Sweden and Great Britain have reduced fuel taxes for natural
gas vehicles.<sup><a href="end.html">55</a></sup>
  Ireland, Belgium and Italy have no excise taxes
on natural gas as a vehicle fuel, and the Netherlands revised
its tax structure to eliminate penalties previously placed on
gaseous fuels.  The application of lower relative taxes on LPG
makes that fuel more attractive, from a price standpoint, than
gasoline or diesel in Ireland, Belgium, Germany, Sweden and the
Czech Republic.<sup><a href="end.html">56</a></sup>  </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Another approach to reducing emissions would
be for a community to organize a market for emission rights, where
those who find ways to reduce emissions below the baseline could
sell the rights to others who face higher control costs.  All
along, air quality would improve, and a primitive but important
set of property rights would emerge.  Emission permit markets
currently exist nationally for sulfur dioxide emission allowances.
 Markets for emission reduction credits are established in regions
throughout California, across several northeastern states, and
in the Mid-Atlantic Regional Air Management Association.
<sup><a href="end.html">57</a></sup>   The
City of Chicago has a burgeoning market underway, and the State
of Texas has approved a state emissions reductions credit market.
<sup><a href="end.html">58</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The U.S.'s struggle to improve air quality
has reached a point where the gains from employing economic incentives,
like a permit market or emission fees and subsidies, are large
enough to cover some meaningful transaction costs.  A plethora
of special taxes, subsidies and other incentive programs are in
place in many states, and the federal government has modulated
fuel taxes to favor or penalize certain fuels.  The rich variety
of state, local and regional programs illustrates the range of
experiments that can take place when we recognize that air pollution
problems are almost always local and regional in nature.  In effect,
states and cities compete for population and economic activities,
both of which are highly mobile.  Those areas that impose burdensome
rules will be punished when people and prospective industrialists
vote with their feet; regions that find lower cost ways to achieve
air quality goals will be rewarded.  The competition among regions
thus leads to many different mixes in taxes, subsidies and permit
markets as each area seeks the most effective and efficient way
to produce clean air.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Federal Incentive Programs</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Actions taken by the federal government to
improve air quality and affect the expansion of the AFV fleet
are just as pervasive as those found at the state and local level.
 There are taxes, subsidies, permit markets and a heavy dose of
mandates.  When considered together, the federal and state programs
seem to reveal a crude effort to encourage the use of cleaner
fuels and cleaner-fuel vehicles.  But unlike local and state governments,
the federal programs offer only a uniform approach that does not
always fit with the various air quality goals sought by communities
facing distinctly different challenges.  In fact, current federal
fuel taxes are not truly based on emissions goals.  Some fuel
types are penalized heavily, relative to others, and programs
based primarily on the goal of providing cleaner air are not particularly
effective.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The political and economic importance of clean
air and energy security has spawned a wide variety of federal
initiatives designed to promote the purchase and use of AFVs.
 Tax credits and deductions are offered for the purchase of AFVs
and certain fuels.  Federal tax law also provides subsidies in
the form of differential excise taxes for those who purchase alternative
fuels.  Income tax deductions are provided under the EPACT for
the incremental costs of engine modification, fuel storage and
delivery systems, and emission control systems (retrofit).  Deductions
are also allowed for refueling facility expenditures.  The following
limits are placed on these deductions:</FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Up to $2,000 for vehicles that weigh less
than 10,000 pounds;</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">$10,000 for vehicles that weigh between
10,000 and 26,000 pounds;</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">$50,000 for trucks and vans over 26,000
pounds and for buses with seating capacity for 20 or more adults;</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">$100,000 for AFV refueling facilities;
and,</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">For flexible-fuel vehicles, only the incremental
costs of qualified items can be deducted.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">EPACT also provides for a 10 percent tax credit
for purchases of electric vehicles, up to a maximum of $4,000
- a credit scheduled to fall by 25 percent in 2002, by one-half
in 2003 and by 75 percent in 2004.<sup><a href="end.html">59</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Alcohol fuels, such as ethanol, also receive
favorable treatment from the federal government.  For example,
the tax code provides income tax credits of 60 cents per gallon
for alcohol content in fuel when used as either a mixture (at
least 10 percent alcohol) or as a straight fuel.  Ethanol producers
are provided a tax credit of 10 cents for each gallon of fuel,
up to 15 million gallons per year, that is sold to buyers who
use it in fuel mixtures or to retail purchasers.  These credits
do not apply to alcohol produced from petroleum, natural gas or
coal (i.e., methanol).  Under current law, these credits are to
expire on January 1, 2001.  The federal tax code also provides
a tax credit of $3.00 per barrel-of-oil equivalent for domestic
production of oil, gas and synthetic fuels derived from nonconventional
sources.<sup><a href="end.html">60</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Federal highway motor fuel taxes differ for
all major conventional and alternative fuels.  The current rate
on gasoline is 18.4 cents per gallon.  The rate for diesel fuel
is 24.4 cents per gallon.  All but 6.9 cents of these taxes is
allocated to the highway trust fund, with the balance earmarked
for deficit reduction and cleanup of underground storage tanks.
Liquefied petroleum gas, liquefied natural gas, methanol (from
natural gas) and 10 percent ethanol fuels are taxed, respectively,
at 18.3 cents, 18.4 cents, 11.4 cents and 13 cents respectively,
which is almost in reverse order of their clean emission characteristics.
However, CNG, which is one of the cleanest burning fuels, is taxed
at the equivalent of 5.6 cents per gallon of gasoline.  Table
1 provides a more complete list of federal motor fuel taxes in
both gallon and gasoline equivalent terms.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Table 1</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">FEDERAL MOTOR FUEL TAXES - AS OF
SEPTEMBER 1994<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
