</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=204><CENTER><FONT FACE="Arial">Mean</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=193><CENTER><FONT FACE="Arial">13.91</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=215><CENTER><FONT FACE="Arial">16.46</FONT></CENTER>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">By making some major assumptions, we can estimate
the consequences of the net tax or subsidy, relative to gasoline,
the federal government provides for the purchase of AFVs and for
the use of alternative fuels.  Assume that the income tax credit
for the purchase of alcohol fuels amounts to six cents per gallon
for 10 percent ethanol blends. Applying this assumption, the first
column of Table 2 shows the approximate effective federal motor
fuel excise rates for the BTU equivalent of gasoline for alternative
fuels after subtracting the alcohol tax credit.  Assuming further
that each vehicle is operated for 120,000 miles (i.e., 10 years
at 12,000 miles per year) and that each vehicle gets 28 miles
per gallon for the BTU equivalent of one gallon of gasoline, the
second column of the table shows the net excise taxes paid by
the vehicle operator.<sup><a href="end.html">61</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">As noted earlier, purchasers of alternative
fuel passenger cars are allowed a tax deduction of $2,000.  If
we assume that automobile buyers are in a 28 percent federal marginal
tax bracket, this deduction reduces the buyer's taxes by $560.
 Electric vehicle buyers are allowed a $4,000 tax credit.  This,
of course, reduces an electric car buyer's taxes by $4,000, regardless
of marginal tax rates.  Using the noted assumptions, the last
column of the table shows the relative advantage given by the
combination of fuel taxes, income tax deductions and credits relative
to gasoline-fueled vehicles.  As indicated, the net value of the
tax reductions is largest for electric vehicles.  Ethanol is some
distance away in second place.  And CNG comes in third.  The value
of the tax reductions for the other fuels is probably too small
to make much difference in consumer behavior.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Even with large tax subsidies, electric vehicles
have not emerged as a competing technology,  and  ethanol  production
 has  not been stimulated in recent years.   With the<BR>
</FONT>
