HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Sunday, 09-Feb-97 12:43:44 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 11-Jul-96 19:50:37 GMT
Content-length: 8126
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head>
<title>V.Emerging AFV Niche Markets</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717"
Vlink="545454" ALINK="#FF0000"><ul><blockquote>
 <a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif"
 align="right" border="0"></a>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">V.  EMERGING AFV NICHE MARKETS<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P><br><p>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Our comparison of AFVs has focused almost exclusively
on light vehicles, and for good reason:  The CAA and EPACT look
to the larger light vehicle fleet for reducing smog and improving
energy security.  For example, EPACT is limited to vehicles weighing
less than 26,000 pounds, which is the beginning weight for large
18-wheelers.  California AFV statutes are limited to vehicles
weighing less than 8,000 pounds.  Furthermore, the vast majority
of research on emissions and costs has been devoted to emerging
light vehicle technologies.  Indeed, when compared with light
vehicles, EPA emission standards for large diesel engines are
at a very rudimentary level.  As indicated by our discussion of
infrastructure, conversion costs, price premiums, vehicle choice
and continued improvement of gasoline-fueled vehicles, penetration
of the light vehicle market by AFVs faces high hurdles.  The growth
experienced by AFVs continues to be found in public and private
fleets where refueling and vehicle choice present little difficulty.
 But the capture of some significant share of the conventional
consumer market is not likely to occur in the foreseeable future.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Many of these seemingly insurmountable challenges
largely disappear when the market for heavy trucks, buses, locomotives
and off-the-road machinery is considered.  Refueling for fixed-schedule
trucks and buses can be conveniently located at terminals, and
the additional tanks required for alternative fuels adds a small
proportional increment to the vehicles' weight.  With almost two
million plying the nation's highways, annually consuming 17 billion
gallons of diesel fuel, heavy trucks present a significant market.
<sup><a href="end.html">118</a></sup>
 </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">A large part of the heavy-duty truck market
is composed of tractor/trailor vehicles weighing more than 26,000
pounds, the limit for EPACT programs.  But there are still significant
federal and state tax incentives for purchasers of heavy-duty
AFVs.  The federal government provides an income tax deduction
of $5,000 for intermediate weight trucks and vans, and a $50,000
tax deduction for vehicles weighing more than 26,000 pounds. Among
states, Arizona provides funds for the conversion of buses; Wisconsin
provides grants for alternative fuel trucks, vans and buses purchased
by municipalities; and, Maryland, Montana and North Dakota provide
state income tax credits to assist the purchase of vehicles weighing
more than 10,000 pounds.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Since heavy-duty vehicles are large fuel consumers,
fuel-cost savings weigh heavily in the balance when AFVs are considered.
 Indeed, in a 1994 report, Weaver and Turner concluded that converting
from diesel to natural gas could be economically justified on
fuel savings alone.<sup><a href="end.html">119</a></sup>
 In a survey of 4,000 fleet operators, 59 percent
reported use of AFVs.<sup><a href="end.html">120</a></sup>
  Of these, 40 percent burned LNG and 39
percent used CNG.  Both user-groups reported substantial fuel
cost savings.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">AFVs offer significant clean-air gains relative
to heavy-duty diesel trucks and vehicles.  In addition to producing
VOCs and nitrogen emissions, conventional diesel engines are heavy
emitters of particulates, CO and sulfur dioxide.  According to
EPA, conversion of 1991 diesel engines to CNG (or LNG) reduces
hydrocarbon emissions by 67 to 80 percent, NOx by 10 percent,
particulates by 40 to 76 percent and CO by 74 percent.
<sup><a href="end.html">121</a></sup>  Switching
to methanol virtually eliminates particulates, but may increase
CO and hydrocarbon emissions.  Movement to LPG eliminates particulates
and reduces CO, but may increase NOx and hydrocarbon emissions.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In a study of 44 LNG heavy-duty vehicle projects
nationwide, Robert Nimocks found some 2,277 LNG heavy-duty vehicles
in service.<sup><a href="end.html">122</a></sup>
  Some 30 additional LNG projects were initiated in
just four years.  Nimocks found that 17 of 51 fleets covered by
his survey were composed of long-distance delivery, less-than-carload
and refuse haulers.  This was concentrated in California and Texas,
where air quality problems are most severe.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Urban buses provide another important niche
market for AFVs.  For example, Brooklyn Union recently announced
that its 12 CNG fueling stations provided the equivalent of one
million gallons of CNG in 1995 to its 2,200 CNG vehicles operating
in New York.<sup><a href="end.html">123</a></sup>
  Included in the fleet are 53 commuter and two shuttle
buses that operate in Brooklyn and Queens.  Some 330 additional
buses are being considered for conversion. The organization estimated
that conversion from diesel fuel eliminated 43 tons of air pollution
in one year.  With 300 alternative-fueled buses, the Houston Metropolitan
Transit Authority operates the world's largest LNG fleet, and
some 10 other transit agencies have converted buses to LNG use,
including Sun Metro in El Paso, which will eventually operate
121 LNG buses.<sup><a href="end.html">124</a>
</sup>  Out of concern about particulate emissions, the
governor of Massachusetts ordered the Massachusetts Bay Transportation
Authority to purchase exclusively buses that use alternative fuels.
<sup><a href="end.html">125</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Throughout our discussion of AFVs, the chicken-and-egg
problem surfaced regularly.  How can people be induced to purchase
AFVs when there is no refueling capability?  Or, how can refueling
infrastructure be built when there is no mass market?  The heavy-duty
truck and vehicle market tends to resolve this problem because
refueling infrastructure can be justified for fleets of urban
buses and operators of heavy-duty trucks that are refueled at
either end of a scheduled run.  The facilities that are built
can then be made available for public use, which strengthens the
overall market for AFVs.  But what about suppliers of engines
and vehicles?  Have they responded to the emerging market forces?</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Major engine and truck producers have responded
to the market for LNG and other alternative-fuel vehicles.  Navistar,
General Motors and Peterbilt are offering LNG-fueled engines.
 Mercedes, General Motors, Flxible and Ikarus offer LNG-fueled
buses, and practically every large engine manufacturer now makes
available LNG and other alternative fuel engines.  Although the
price premium for equipping a heavy-duty truck or bus with an
alternative-fuel engine runs as much as $60,000, the gain in fuel
and operating costs comes close to offsetting the premium. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In addition to these niche players, a potential
market may be developing for locomotives and operators of mining
machinery and ore carriers.  Again, refueling presents a smaller
challenge than in the light-vehicle market.  Here too, the gains
from fuel cost savings go a long way toward offsetting conversion
costs and purchase premiums.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The evidence we have compiled indicates that
AFVs are a viable force in the heavy-duty market.  Again, LNG
and CNG appear to be the major contenders in this market.  Regional
pressures to reduce air emissions form part of the stimulus, but
sheer economic forces push in the direction of alternative fuels
in these significant niche markets.  AFVs can surely be a component
of Environmental Innovation Areas. </FONT>
<P>
<a href="sect6.html">Next Section: Environmental Innovation Areas</a><p>
<a href="sect4.html">Previous Section: AFV Emission And Cost Characteristics</a><p>
<a href="end.html">End Notes</a>
</BODY>
</HTML>
