<HEAD>
<TITLE>Entrepreneurs and Elections '96 </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="/sbsc/sbsmall.gif">
<p>
<CENTER><H2>Entrepreneurs and Elections '96: <br>A Candidate's Handbook to Critical Small Business Issues<br> February 1996</H2></CENTER>
<P>
<br>
<hr>
<center>
<b>Table of Contents</b>
</center>
<ul>
<li><a href="#one">Introduction</a>
<li><a href="#two">The Impact of Small Business and Entrepreneurs on the Economy</a>
<li><a href="#three">A Pro-Entrepreneur Tax System</a>
<li><a href="#four">I. Immediate Reform</a>
<li><a href="#five">II. Tax overhaul</a>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>

<blockquote>
<a name="one"><CENTER><H3>Introduction</a></H3></CENTER>
During election campaigns, special interests attempt to push, pull, cajole, and maneuver candidates into supporting their narrow agendas.  Under such pressures and in the heat of a campaign, candidates can succumb to such narrow interests and lose sight of those policies and actions that serve all entrepreneurs and the economy best.
<p> 
 Unfortunately, small but vocal parts of the business community can be listed among these special interests.  They can be found supporting positions that may promote their own particular, short-term interests, but at the cost of business and the economy at large.
Therefore, the Small Business Survival (SBS) Foundation has undertaken an effort to educate candidates, along with the media, businesses, entrepreneurs, and citizens, as to the policies that boost entrepreneurship, investment, and economic growth.  This booklet -- "Entrepreneurs and Elections '96: A Candidate's Handbook to Critical Small Business Issues" -- will be the very cornerstone of SBS Foundation's education efforts for the upcoming year.
<P>
After reading through this booklet, candidates will gain some insights as to how to think in economic terms.  Many candidates have little trouble thinking politically, but often are guilty of leaving sound economics out of their policy platforms.  However, economics cannot and should not be left out of any campaign effort.  When politicians do forget economics, the consequences can be severe, whether on the campaign trail or upon taking elected office.
<p>
In the end, candidates need to remember that sound economics makes for sound politics, and ultimately sound governing.  In the end, sound economics dictates removing government-imposed hurdles to entrepreneurship and small business success.<P>
<hr>
<a name="two"><H3><CENTER>The Impact of Small Business and Entrepreneurs on the Economy</a></CENTER></H3>
Why should candidates be concerned about small business and entrepreneurs?  It is an important question that must be answered here, at the outset; otherwise, the rest of this publication becomes irrelevant.  (See related box on pages 8-9.)<P>
The importance of small business and entrepreneurial activity in the economy is overwhelming.  Four fundamental reasons stand out:
First, entrepreneurs are the source of dynamism and growth in any economy.  They are the risk takers without which an economy would stagnate and eventually decline.  
<p>
Entrepreneurs keep the economy vibrant and growing.  As I noted recently in The Freeman: "The critical role of the entrepreneur in the economy is to see added value where others have failed to do so -- to enhance production and/or efficiency.  That is, to fulfill the essence of Say's Law -- that supply creates demand.  In turn, one can identify numerous types of entrepreneurship.  The Schumpeterian entrepreneur, named for economist Joseph Schumpeter and his notion of 'creative destruction,' offers innovations or inventions that can transform entire industries and economies.  Other entrepreneurs offer improvements in the way particular firms perform through, perhaps, different management or production structures; while still others simply see better ways of doing things and start their own businesses.  Additional entrepreneurs are at work in the investment community.  For example, an investment banker or corporate raider might see added value through a proposed corporate merger or takeover.  Then there are the venture capitalists willing to risk their own investment dollars supporting an idea, invention, innovation, or new business."2  
<p>
Second, hundreds of thousands of individuals start up their own businesses each year.  Individuals dip into the entrepreneurial waters for a variety of reasons.  Most prominent remains the American dream of owning and succeeding with one's own enterprise -- the self-made man or woman, if you will.  Financial independence, the satisfaction of bringing a new product or service to market, and improving upon what your competitors have done, all co-mingle to play a role in stirring the entrepreneurial spirit.<P>
In addition, the bureaucracies and often perverse incentive structures at many large companies, as well as corporate restructurings and downsizings, have led, or sometimes forced, individuals to become entrepreneurs -- to start up their own small businesses.  According to the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics, in 1994, some 500,000 Americans lost their jobs due to downsizing, for a total of 4.4 million in the past 15 years.
<p>
Lastly, proper public policy steps (explained in more detail throughout the remainder of this booklet) boost incentives for entrepreneurship and venture capital investment.<P>
Figure 1 traces new business incorporations from 1967 to 1994.  Incorporations had been on a fairly steady rise from 1967 through 1986 (with drops in 1970, 1974, and 1982), but steadily declined from 1987 through 1991.  The 1986 peak of 702,738 was only reached again in 1993, when incorporations hit 706,537, then rising to 741,657 in 1994.
<P>
Figure 2 shows annual percent changes in new business incorporations from 1968 to 1994.  Again, the 1987 to 1991 period is quite striking.
Figure 3 offers a broader picture of entrepreneurship.  It traces the establishment of new firms between 1983 and 1993.  Steady growth occurred from 1983 to 1987, with a meandering pattern since.  Figure 4 puts these numbers in percentage growth terms.<P>
Figure 5 offers another view of the growth in the number of U.S. businesses.  It shows the annual percentage increase in nonfarm business tax returns -- including corporations, partnerships, and proprietorships -- for 1981 to 1993.<P>
However, the true spirit of American individualism and entrepreneurship may be best captured by the "one man" business.  Between 1970 and 1991, the number of sole proprietorships filing tax returns leapt from 5.7 million to 15.2 million -- an increase of 167 percent.  The United States truly is the land of opportunity and entrepreneurship.<P>
The millions of entrepreneurs represented by these charts and numbers benefit consumers and the economy by introducing new products and services, more choices, enhanced competition, and greater efficiencies to the marketplace.  And they do all this at considerable economic peril.  The risks of starting up, investing in, and owning and operating a business run high.<P>
Third, small businesses create the bulk of new jobs.  As many large firms downsize in order to compete in the global economy, job creation falls to small business.  This has been the case for at least the past decade and a half, with the trend continuing today.<P>
According to Dun & Bradstreet's 1995 employment survey, firms with fewer than 100 employees will account for 66 percent of all new jobs created in 1995, with 50 percent of all employment gains coming in firms with fewer than 20 employees.  Firms with fewer than 500 employees will account for 84 percent of all new jobs created.<P>
Figure 6 shows the small business share of total private sector employment (1991 data latest available).  Fifty-three percent of all private-sector employees work in firms with less than 500 employees; 39 percent work in enterprises with less than 100 employees; and 20 percent in businesses of less than 20 employees.<P>
Finally, the best agenda for small business is the best agenda for the nation as a whole.  Since small business produces the bulk of new jobs; employs a majority of U.S. workers; includes in its ranks corporations, partnerships, and sole proprietorships; and remains a key source of dynamism and innovation in the economy; then what's good for small business and the entrepreneur is good for the nation.  The following pages spell out the true small business agenda.<P>
<hr>
<a name="three">
<H3><CENTER>A Pro-Entrepreneur Tax System</a></CENTER></H3>
There is no greater burden faced by entrepreneurs than taxation.  A recent Small Business Survival Committee (SBSC) poll found that small business owners identify the IRS by far as the most burdensome federal government agency.  <P>
While taxes always play a critical part in every election, they promise to be particularly important in 1996.  A complete reform of our tax system is now under serious consideration in our nation's capital.  Tax overhaul promises to become a prominent aspect of every major political race in America -- including all House and Senate contests and especially the race for the White House.  Overhauling our current tax system and lowering the tax burden on businesses and individuals will boost economic growth and opportunity -- a positive message transcending all income levels.<P>
In an effort to help clarify the tax overhaul debate now upon us, SBS Foundation published a booklet in June 1995 entitled "The Great Tax Debate: Making Sense of Competing Tax Plans."  The major tax reform proposals were evaluated according to eight criteria of sound taxation, summarized as follows:<ul><P>
<li> Low Flat Tax Rate to Promote Economic Growth - the lower and more proportional, or flatter, the tax rate system the better.  
<li> No Taxation of Capital - taxing returns on investment and savings makes absolutely no economic sense.  
<li> Inflation Factor - the detrimental effects of inflation should be factored into any tax system's design. No additional incentive for the monetary authority to inflate should be provided by the tax system.  
<li> Clarity - the clearer the tax system the better.  The best tax system makes clear how much is owed, who is paying, and when the tax is being paid.  
<li> Simplicity - tax payments should be made as easy and as simple as possible for the taxpayer without any loss of clarity.  
<li> Limited Bureaucracy and Intrusiveness - the fewer tax collectors and the more limited their powers the better.
<li> Minimize Incentives for Tax Avoidance - taxes should be low enough so as to not provide significant incentives for avoidance.  
<li> No Additional Boost to Government Spending - a tax system's design should not make it any easier for government to increase expenditures. </ul><p>
Based on these eight principles, a sound tax system -- one which allows entrepreneurs to flourish and the economy to grow -- can be established.  The following proposals for a pro-entrepreneur tax system are broken into two sections -- the first being necessary reforms under our current federal tax structure, while the second outlines ideas for completely overhauling the tax system. 
<P>
<hr>
<H3><CENTER><a name="four">I. Immediate Reforms</a></CENTER></H3>
<ul><li><b> Capital Gains Taxes.</b>  At the time of this writing, Congress was moving to cut the capital gains tax by instituting a 50-percent exclusion from taxation for individuals -- lowering the top rate from 28 percent to 19.8 percent -- as well as lowering the corporate rate to 28 percent.  If passed, these are positive steps that would help the U.S. economy regain ground lost in terms of stifled entrepreneurship after the capital gains tax was increased by 40 percent under the 1986 Tax Reform Act.  Figures 1 through 5 reflect the drop off in entrepreneurial activity after the 1986 capital gains tax hike.  However, while moving in the right direction, this capital gains tax cut remains inadequate.<P>
In order to boost incentives for investment and risk taking -- the engines of economic growth -- the capital gains tax should be eliminated.  Considering the high risks involved with starting up and expanding a business, eliminating the capital gains tax is perhaps the most pro-entrepreneur tax initiative a candidate or elected official can support.  By removing the considerable hurdle of capital gains taxation, high risks can be offset by at least the opportunity for significant returns.  Without such an opportunity, investment, entrepreneurship, economic growth, and job creation suffer.<P>
At minimum, a candidate should support indexation of capital gains for inflation.  Taxing illusory gains due to inflation is unfair and economically counter-productive.  Indeed, the real capital gains tax rate jumps considerably when inflation is factored into the equation.  In fact, in many instances, taxes can be paid on an inflation-adjusted capital loss.  Can there be any doubt as to the detrimental effects of a non-indexed capital gains tax?<P>
Of course, supporting capital gains tax reduction often opens candidates up to bankrupt, class-warfare criticisms.  The answers to such levies are simple and straightforward.<P><ul>
<li>Enhanced incentives for investment and entrepreneurship boost economic growth and job creation.
<li>Many of our international competitors tax capital gains far more lightly than does the United States.  For example, Germany, Hong Kong and the Netherlands do not tax long-term capital gains at all.  Even nations with higher nominal capital gains rates than the U.S. -- like Australia and the United Kingdom -- index gains for inflation, thereby effectively having lower real capital gains tax rates.
<li>Investors and entrepreneurs spend and invest funds far more efficiently than do government bureaucrats.
<li>The direct tax benefits of capital gains tax reduction are claimed by individuals across the income spectrum.  For example, the latest figures provided by Investor's Business Daily (November 20, 1995) show that in 1993, 84 percent of income earners claiming capital gains had total incomes of less than $100,000.  Incomes of less than $50,000 laid claim to 57 percent of all returns claiming capital gains.  <P></ul>
Critics counter that only 29.7 percent of capital gains income fell to earners with total incomes of less than $100,000, with the rest going to the "rich."  Putting aside the fact that the "rich" put their money to better use than government bureaucrats, one has to generally question this "rich" label.  After all, if one extracts capital gains from total income to gain a better understanding of the standard income levels of individuals, then over 52 percent of capital gains income were claimed by income earners with less than $100,000 in non-capital-gains income.<P>
The case for eliminating the capital gains tax stands tallest when one understands and argues that growth will be enhanced, incomes increased, and job creation boosted as a result.  Economic growth is a strong campaign message.<P>
<li> <STRONG>Estate Taxes.</STRONG>  At the time this booklet was being written, Congress agreed to raise the exemption under the estate tax from $600,000 to $750,000, and for certain "family-owned" businesses, the first $1 million in value would be exempt and a 40-percent tax exclusion applied to the $1 million to $2.5 million value range.  Once again, if agreed to by President Clinton, these initiatives are positive but insufficient.<P>
Unfortunately, 60 percent of family-owned businesses fail to survive to a second generation, with 90 percent never seeing a third.  The estate tax plays a significant role in the demise of family businesses.  In effect, the estate tax amounts to a hostile takeover of businesses and assets by the government -- with a top rate of 55 percent, plus another 5 percent for very large estates.  <P>
Of course, no economic reason can be found to justify estate and inheritance taxes.  The unfairness of individuals paying taxes their entire lives only to have have their assets raided by the government at death is manifest.  Such levies are based solely on class warfare impulses and government's incessant drive to root out more and more revenues.  Of course, in the meantime, the estate tax deprives businesses of precious capital and creates disincentives for investing in and expanding family businesses.
<P>
Estate taxes generate a mere one percent of government revenues with most of that wiped out by litigation and administrative costs.  This is a high price to pay for the destruction of thousands of businesses and jobs each year.<P>
Estate and inheritance taxes make absolutely no economic sense whatsoever, and should be eliminated. <P>
<li> <STRONG>The Bush and Clinton Tax Increases.</STRONG>  The tax increases of both the Bush and Clinton administrations diverted resources away from productive private-sector ventures and made working, saving, investing, and risk taking more costly.  Indeed, an April/May 1994 Small Business Survival Committee (SBSC) survey of 500 small businesses found that a total of 69 percent of respondents declared that the Clinton tax hikes forced them to either raise prices, postpone expansion, terminate at least one employee, or some combination of these actions.  <P>
The Bush and Clinton tax increases should be rolled back.  Of particular importance is reducing income tax rates to their former levels -- for example, dropping the top individual rate back to 28 percent from its current level of 39.6 percent.<P>
<li> <STRONG>Constitutional Protections for Taxpayers. </STRONG> Constitutional protections are needed for the American taxpayer.  Ever increasing taxes destroy the spirit of entrepreneurship, weigh down the economy, and infringe upon liberty.  A "Taxpayer Protection Constitutional Amendment" would do the following: <P>
Ban retroactive tax increases.  President Clinton's 1993 tax increase was made retroactive to the beginning of that year -- before he even took office.  Individuals, entrepreneurs, and businesses need some semblance of stability when it comes to taxation for their own planning purposes.  In contrast, retroactive tax hikes create significant instability.  The unfairness and economically destructive nature of retroactive tax increases is clear.  <P>
Require a two-thirds super-majority vote in both houses of Congress in order to increase current taxes and fees, or to impose new ones.  As Chief Justice John Marshall warned: "The power to tax involves the power to destroy."  Perhaps no greater truth was ever uttered regarding the impact of taxation.  
The Constitution protects us from governmental abuses.  The Founding Fathers never envisioned government growing to the massive level it has today; nor the current burdensome levels of taxation.  Placing a super-majority vote requirement on Congress in order to raise taxes not only makes for sound economics, but fits neatly into the Constitution's purpose of limiting governmental powers.<P>
<li> <STRONG>Independent Contractors. </STRONG> The question of who is or is not classified by the IRS as an independent contractor has long concerned small businesses and the self-employed.  The IRS offers a 20-point criteria which is vague and complex.  <P>
Reclassifications by the IRS are standard and costly.  For example, according to SBS Foundation President Karen Kerrigan in a recent column in the American City Business Journals, "[T]he IRS has reclassified 439,000 independent workers since the mid 1980s, resulting in the collection of $678 million in taxes and fines."<P>
The IRS's criteria for determining who is an independent contractor must be clarified and simplified.  For example, recent legislation by Rep. Jon Christensen (R-Neb.) offered a fairly straightforward three-part test requiring that an independent contractor demonstrate independence, investment in his business, and a written agreement between parties. </ul><P>
<hr>
<H3><CENTER><a name="five">II. Tax Overhaul.</a></CENTER></H3>
As already noted, the complete overhaul of the U.S. tax system is now under serious consideration, and without a doubt, will play a significant part in the 1996 political debates.  In "The Great Tax Debate," the SBS Foundation scored and ranked the various tax overhaul plans.  <P>
According to our eight criteria for a sound tax system, the flat tax scored highest followed closely by a national retail sales tax, with a value-added tax (VAT), the consumed-income tax, and our current system trailing well behind.  Thankfully, the two systems ranked best in "The Great Tax Debate" -- the flat tax and a national retail sales tax -- currently are receiving extensive consideration and examination by tax experts, policy makers, and elected officials.<P>
Though the SBS Foundation has provided a complete review of the various tax overhaul proposals in "The Great Tax Debate," the importance of this issue for the 1996 elections dictates that we summarize here how the flat tax and national retail sales tax measure up to our eight criteria for sound taxation.<P>
<STRONG>THE FLAT TAX </STRONG><ul><P>
<li><STRONG> Low Flat Tax Rate to Promote Economic Growth.</STRONG>  Generally under consideration right now is a flat tax that actually is a two-rate tax system -- no tax on income up to a certain level and then a flat rate on all income earned above that level.  The rate most often cited by reformers is 17 percent.  A flat tax of 17 percent -- preferably less -- would greatly reduce tax-based disincentives for working and risk taking.
<li><STRONG> No Taxation of Capital.</STRONG>  The flat tax would not tax earnings from investment and saving at all -- no taxation of capital gains, dividends, or interest <p><br>
<p><br>
<center>
| <a href="/sbsc/">Home</a> |</center>
<p><br>
</body>
</html>
