</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Keating Testimony:  Reforming OSHA</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><i>June 28, 1995</i><hr>
<h3>Reforming OSHA</h3> 
<b>Testimony by<br>
 Raymond J. Keating<br> 
Chief Economist<br>
Small Business Survival Committee<P>

before the <br>
Subcommittee on Workforce Protections<br>Committee on Economic and Educational Opportunities<P>U.S. House of 
Representatives</b></center>
<hr>
<P>	


Mr. Chairman and Members of the Subcommittee, I thank you for inviting me here today to discuss the Safety and Health Improvement and Regulatory Reform Act of 1995, and OSHA  reform in general.  My name is Ray Keating, and I am chief economist for the Small Business Survival Committee, a small business advocacy organization with over 40,000 members across the nation.<P>	

How could anyone find fault with a government agency named the "Occupational Safety and Health Administration"?  However, in fact, there is much to find fault with at OSHA.  OSHA has become a burdensome regulatory body which seems to be more concerned with paper pushing and imposing fines rather than with assisting businesses in establishing safer working environments. This is the view justifiably held by many business owners and operators, including most of the Small Business Survival Committee's 40,000 members.  Indeed, a recent nationwide survey of 500 small businesses sponsored by SBSC revealed that OSHA ranked with the IRS and the EPA as the most burdensome federal agencies.<P>	

Contrary to the view of OSHA's most enthusiastic proponents, the private sector possesses every incentive to maintain a safe and healthy working environment for employees.  Indeed, beyond a commonly held concern for one's employees, the financial incentives for safety are substantial.  I.e., safety pays.  "Safety" costs for U.S. business in 1992 were estimated in excess of $200 billion, far outweighing the $72 million in OSHA citations.<P>	

Workplaces that are not safe have always been and remain the exception rather than the rule.  OSHA acts under the opposite assumption, thereby imposing significant and unnecessary costs on business and the economy.  Such costs translate into less entrepreneurship, slower economic growth, and fewer jobs.  It is time that OSHA's regulations and activities reflect the fact that most businesses do indeed maintain "safe and healthful working conditions."<P>	The evidence that OSHA has gone far astray from an educational, advisory and cooperative relationship with business is substantial.  Indeed, OSHA's concern for real safety seems lost in a bureaucratic and regulatory haze of paperwork, citation quotas, and remarkably inane regulations.  I have outlined some of these developments, along with other related facts about OSHA regulations and expenditures, in the accompanying paper entitled "Warning: OSHA Can Be Hazardous to the Nation's Economic Health."  I ask that this short analysis be submitted into the record.<P>	

There are three points from this analysis I would like to mention here.  First, OSHA manages to combine two of the worst aspects of government regulatory bodies.  It creates an incredible paperwork burden on U.S. business.  In 1994, seven of the top ten most frequent OSHA citations were related to paperwork.  OSHA has perfected the government "make work" scheme -- generate a blizzard of paperwork regulations and then fine businesses for not complying.<P>	

Second, a prevailing problem with government regulation and inspections of any industry or workplace is that most, if not all, regulators are not experts in particular industries.  If they were experts, one would expect that they would hold productive, private sector jobs.  They are government bureaucrats.  Bureaucrats know paperwork.  Hence, the most cited violations by OSHA are paperwork related.  <P>	

Third, the gross budget authority for OSHA was over $298 million in 1994.  Tax dollars spent on federal enforcement and state programs (administering and enforcing state standards) account for 70 percent of OSHA's budget.  As with many of OSHA's other activities, I think this reflects an attitude of confrontation towards rather than cooperation with business.<P>	Even after one notes the many OSHA horror stories, regulations, paperwork burdens, and costs, some still claim that OSHA's benefits outweigh its many costs.  For example, in a May 16, 1995 speech, President Clinton linked OSHA with reduced workplace deaths.  He stated: "The Occupational Safety and Health Administration has been at work in this cause since it was created with bipartisan support in 1970.  Since that time, workplace deaths have been cut in half."<P>

Of course, workplace deaths were on the decline long before OSHA was created.  Fewer workplace deaths reflect many changes in our economy -- greater automation, shift in employment from manufacturing to services, leaps in technology, enhanced knowledge, et al.  There exists no clear and substantial evidence that OSHA has played any significant role in preventing workplace injuries or death.<P>	

In light of these facts, SBSC supports Representative Cass Ballenger's "Safety and Health Improvement and Regulatory Reform Act of 1995."  It offers many real, positive OSHA reforms.  In particular, I'd like to note the following:<P>
<ul>
<LI> A Voluntary Compliance Program (VCP) allowing any employer to utilize an approved private-sector safety and health consultant for safety and health reviews.  Participants in the VCP would be exempt from random OSHA inspections for up to one year.  	Such a reform will help to alleviate the problem of lack of expertise among OSHA inspectors.  By essentially contracting out these inspections to the private sector, private firms, including perhaps insurance companies, will have clear incentives to become industry experts, more so than government bureaucrats today.<P>

<LI> An opportunity for an employer to correct alleged safety and health violations before a citation is issued, unless a fatality or serious injury occurred.  With so many OSHA rules and regulations, allowing employers to correct alleged violations before being fined is a fair, much-needed reform.  This reform also should reduce OSHA's own paperwork burden.<P>

<LI> Eliminates penalties for posting and paperwork violations, except where a direct threat of injury or an intent to deceive OSHA exist.  This will considerably rollback OSHA's ability to impose frivolous penalties on employers, saving millions of dollars annually.<P>

<LI> Formally codifies the small business OSHA exemption 
from routine safety inspections, and expands it to firms with  50 or fewer employees that have below average injury rates.<P><LI> Requires the application of cost benefit, risk assessment, and regulatory impact analyses to OSHA regulations.  <P>

<LI> Reserves at least 50 percent of the OSHA budget for consultation, training, education, and compliance assistance programs.  This would be a good first step toward making OSHA a more cooperative federal agency.<P>

<LI> Seeks to apply stricter, non-arbitrary criteria in 
order for OSHA to levy fines in excess of $7,000.<P>

<LI> Requires that employees first go to employers to 
redress workplace problems before approaching OSHA.  Such a measure should greatly reduce frivolous and harassing complaints by employees who are disgruntled or in the midst of a labor dispute.<P>

<LI> Consolidates the Mine Safety and Health Administration with OSHA, and eliminates the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health.  SBSC is a strong supporter of all efforts to eliminate waste and duplication in government, and to reduce government expenditures.<P>	These OSHA reforms and others included in Representative Ballenger's bill amount to much more than rhetoric about "reinventing" government.  They are real reforms that make for a somewhat saner regulatory regime, and will positively impact U.S. businesses and the economy.
<P>	</ul>
A new regulatory framework is needed in the United States.  One that no longer incorrectly assumes that business owners are merely callous exploiters of labor, but recognizes them as the risk takers, job creators, innovators, and producers they actually are.  If the U.S. economy is to compete and succeed in the twenty-first century, government's heavy hand of over-regulation must be lifted.  Reforming OSHA is a good start which has SBSC's full support.<P>

I thank the Committee, once again, for inviting me here today.  I will be glad to answer any questions you might have, and I offer SBSC's assistance in your efforts to provide for a saner regulatory environment in the United States.<P>
<P><P>
<center>[ <a href="/sbsc/home.html">SBSC Home</a> | <a href="/sbsc/i-ct.html">SBSC Congressional Testimony</a> ]</body></html>



