<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="/sbsc/sbsmall.gif">
<p>
<center>
<h2>
Carolan & Keating -- October 28, 1996<br>
Pre-Election Round-Up<br>
</h2>
<p>
<h3>
by Matthew Carolan and Raymond J. Keating<br>
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<blockquote>
<dd>A few observations before the November 5 election:
<ul>
<li>C&K's most interesting New York races to watch:<ol><li>Top notch Republican, Conservative, and Right-to-Life candidate Sue Wittig in New York's 26th CD has a real shot to topple nationally known green Democrat Maurice Hinchey; <li>Democratic Party honcho Judith Hope pins party hopes on Carolyn McCarthy -- whose husband was killed, and son shot in LIRR massacre -- in her race against Republican Dan Frisa in Long Island's 4th CD. McCarthy, a nice woman, knows nothing about the issues, including assault weapons ban she touts.  Big sympathy vote gives her the lead, though final Frisa mail blitz to undecideds could pull out the race in a conservative district.</ol>
<li>Missing: Governor of New York.  Governor Pataki has been seen promoting environmental pork bond act, catching a flight to Central Europe, and at Yankee Stadium.  However, the Dole for President campaign can't seem to find him.  Indeed, New York Republican lemmings must regret having followed their leader Senator D'Amato over the Dole cliff.
<li>It's a shame that Bob Dole and Jack Kemp have run an unbelievably inept presidential campaign and will lose on November 5.  The Dole-Kemp economic plan would have provided much-needed tax and regulatory relief for New York taxpayers, entrepreneurs and businesses.  The Dole-Kemp 15 percent across-the-board income tax reduction and the $500 per child tax credit would have saved New York families an estimated $1,646 per year on average.  The 50 percent cut in the capital gains tax, along with inflation indexing, would have provided a significant boost to investment, risk taking and economic growth.  Throw in some real regulatory and legal reform, and this Dole-Kemp plan makes the Pataki tax cuts look puny.  But New York will help send Clinton back to the White House, with real tax and regulatory reform put off until the next century.
<li>Throughout his career, Jack Kemp has enthusiastically reached out to black Americans and other minorities with a market-oriented agenda, while many others in his party neglected the minority vote.  We applaud Kemp's efforts. However, during recent weeks of this presidential contest, when Dole-Kemp can't even shore up the traditional GOP base, one has to wonder why Kemp still spends so much time in places like Harlem.  The numbers -- e.g., one percentage point of the black vote translates into roughly 0.1 percentage point of the total vote -- make it difficult to justify Kemp's regular campaigning in these final days in inner cities.  
<li>As is increasingly the case, New York Conservative Party turns out to be a mixed bag this year.  "Contract with New York" turns out to be a non-starter, as anti-Gingrich sentiment stifles talk of programmatic reform. However, Conservative Party legislative ratings for this year do show a decided shift to the right under Pataki, with even liberals like Sheldon Silver voting 50 percent conservative.  Perhaps lack of wedge issues produced grade inflation? Meanwhile, Tom Long, brother of Conservative Party Chairman Mike Long, gives Queens County Conservative Party endorsement in New York's 7th CD to fanatical pro-choice Republican Rose Birtley, running against pro-life Democrat Tom Manton by touting her support of partial-birth abortion.  Would Queens conservatives endorse similar extremists if they supported a progressive income tax or cutting patronage jobs for conservative lackeys?  Perhaps we don't want to know the answer to that question. Kudos, however, to Westchester conservatives for giving line to Joe DioGuardi, and not incumbent liberal GOPer Sue Kelly in 19th CD.  Kelly, for some undisclosed reason, warrants the undying, arm-twisting support of Speaker Newt Gingrich.
<li>Memo to Long Island Congressman Peter King: Gerry Adams called. He wants to congratulate you for taking on Louis Farrakhan so courageously in your campaign literature.
<li>For once, C&K agrees with the New York Democratic Party.  They recently asserted that Senator D'Amato's ads for the environmental pork bond act essentially amount to political shilling to re-build Senator Pothole's reputation.
<li>Ron Lauder seems to be suffering from a split personality.  On the one hand, he fights the good fight to keep New York City's term limits in tact.  On the other hand, according to The New York Times, Lauder forked over $25,000 to support the environmental pork bond act.
<li>After hockey's Devils won a Stanley Cup, they got a new arena deal from New Jersey officials.  Likewise, the Yankees' World Series victory will seal the deal for a new $1 billion-plus, taxpayer-financed Yankee Stadium.
<li>Conservative opposition to the environmental pork bond act has not exactly been robust.  Of course, New York's unprincipled business groups largely support this $1.75 billion boost in New York debt.  Some supporters even claim that the bond act will create tens of thousands of jobs!  Will New York political and community leaders ever understand that only a robust private sector creates wealth and jobs?  We doubt it.
</ul>
<p>
</pre>
Matthew Carolan is executive editor of National Review.  Raymond J. Keating serves as chief economist for the Small Business Survival Committee. The views expressed are their own.  Copyright 1996.
<p>
<center>
</blockquote>
