<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Carolyn and Keating</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="/sbsc/sbsmall.gif">
<P>
<center>
<h2>
Carolan & Keating -- September 2, 1996<BR>
Term Limits: City and State<BR>
</h2>
<P>
<h3>
by Matthew Carolan and Raymond J. Keating<BR>
</h3>
<P>
</center>
<blockquote>
     You know liberalism is in trouble when even New York City
Council members, some of the state's most hard&#173;left politicos,
are aping Bill Clinton by cloaking themselves in the mantle of
conservatism.  Just look at their current attempt to protect their
jobs with their &quot;responsible&quot; version of term limits
this fall.
<P>
     Recall that in 1993, New Yorkers voted 60 percent to 40 percent
to impose limits on their Council members of two terms of four
years each.  Now the Council is trying to weasel out from under
the law, offering a referendum to change the limits from eight
years to 12, and to &quot;restart the clock&quot; on their careers
so that many of them won't have to leave until 2007.  Council
Speaker and perpetual politician Peter Vallone argues that without
these changes there will be &quot;absolute chaos,&quot; as &quot;inexperienced&quot;
politicians take over the whole Council at once.
<P>
     Anyone who follows the City Council knows what its &quot;experience&quot;
is like. This past year the New York Post offered a shocking expose
of Council members' poor attendance records, uncouth manner, and
lack of initiative.  Priscilla Wooten, Democrat from Brooklyn,
recently summarized her 14&#173;year career in one line: &quot;I
just know how to play the game.&quot;
<P>
     A cadre of unelected special interests &#173;&#173; labor
unions, ethnic militants, real estate developers, and party bosses
&#173;&#173; help keep the same old hacks in power, bleeding the
city and state.  Much fault lies also with New Yorkers, who either
benefit from Council greed or don't turn out to vote.  Yet, even
the most principled voter can't undo this mess if given only a
&quot;choice&quot; of candidates dominated by those interests.
<P>
     Term limits takes the &quot;career&quot; out of politics,
offering a government based on ideas rather than personal friendships
and payoffs.  Term limits have been recommended by Thomas Jefferson,
John Adams, Ben Franklin, Abraham Lincoln, Harry Truman, and Dwight
Eisenhower.  Studies by the CATO Institute show a direct correlation
between length in office and increased pork&#173;barrel spending.
<P>
     According to U.S. Term Limits, 21 states, mostly out West
where big government is less in vogue, have instituted term limits
for their state legislators.  Over 3,000 localities across the
U.S. now have limits, with 26 localities in New York State (10
passing limits in 1993 alone).  And in major cities like New Orleans
and Kansas City, as Ronald Lauder points out, term limits have
not produced any negative consequences.
<P>
     Expect the battle in New York City to get personal.  Desperate
politicians are sure to try to muddy the waters, accusing millionaire
Lauder &#173;&#173; a prime mover behind New York's term limits
movement &#173;&#173; of what they themselves are guilty of: &quot;allowing
money to influence the political process.&quot;   Allen Roth,
a spokesman for Mr. Lauder, notes: &quot;As long as the voters
know that they now have the term limits they want, they won't
accept the Council's arguments.&quot;
<P>
     Internal polls for the term limits movement show opposition
to the Council's changes stands at 70 percent.  The most recent
New York Post poll shows support for the current limits at 63
percent to 18 percent.     And informed sources also tell us that
a surprising number of influential liberals are soon to denounce
the Council's term&#173;limits revision.  Mr. Lauder is going
to spend &quot;whatever it takes&quot; to defeat the new initiative.
 Even the New York Times, which does not support term limits,
has accused Vallone of trying to do an &quot;end run&quot; around
the will of the voters.  Expect a major defeat for the Council
this fall.
<P>
     Can conservatives parlay the scalping of Mr. Vallone into
something more?  The Conservative Party's &quot;Contract with
New York&quot; calls for term limits as part of the overall strategy
to win the statehouse this year.  And a poll conducted recently
by Fabrizio&#173; McLaughlin and Associates shows that voters
are more likely, by a margin of 72 percent to 10 percent, to support
a candidate who pledges to limit his own term.  Seems like a golden
opportunity for the New York GOP, which has been trying to win
the Assembly for years. 
<P>
     We're not so sure, however, that the current Republican leadership
are at all interested.  (After all, New York Republicans seems
as enthralled with doling out billions in pork dollars each year
as Democrats are.)  And under current law, no referendum to amend
the state constitution can go to the voters before the politicians
in Albany deign to support it on two separate legislative sessions.
 That's unlikely.
<P>
     Conservative activists need to put the heat on Governor Pataki,
who allegedly supports term limits.  If Pataki fails to make the
case for a term limits referendum &#173;&#173; a golden opportunity
for Assembly candidates this fall &#173;&#173; he would clearly
line up on the side of pork over principle.  A sufficient reason,
we think, for the Conservative Party leaders (who despise pork)
to run their own gubernatorial candidate in 1998.
<P>
_____________________________________
<P>
Matthew Carolan is executive editor of National Review.  Raymond
J. Keating is chief economist for the Small Business Survival
Committee.  The opinions expressed are their own.
<P>
Copyright (1996).<BR>
<BR>
<p>
