<html>
<head>
<title>Carolan & Keating - July 29, 1996</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<img src="/sbsc/sbsmall.gif">
<p>
<center><h2>Carolan & Keating - July 29, 1996</h2><p>
<br>
<h3><i>Chemical Weapons in New York?</i></h3><p>

<b>by Matthew Carolan and Raymond J. Keating</b></center>
<p><br>
<blockquote>
<hr>
The story line includes chemical weapons, officials from the Hague, and the threat of 
international espionage for hundreds of businesses in New York.  It's not a James Bond film or 
the latest Tom Clancy page-turner, nor is it the paranoid tale of some militia group.
This is the story of the Chemical Weapons Convention (CWC) -- an international treaty 
set to come before the U.S. Senate for ratification by September 14.  The CWC's stated purpose 
is to ban the production and stockpiling of chemical weapons.  Unfortunately, it falls far short of 
such vaunted goals while imposing considerable costs.  <p>
The CWC fails the most basic tests of an arms control treaty.  It is non-enforceable, 
non-verifiable, and does not serve the national interest.  Rogue states will still possess chemical 
weapons; small, mobile production facilities will elude detection; and the U.S. will lose its edge 
in terms of deterrence powers and the development of counter-measures.  		After all, 
proving the "non-existence" of something is an absurd and dangerous requirement on which to 
base a treaty.  As former Reagan Defense Department officials Douglas Feith and Frank Gaffney 
Jr. have noted: "The trouble is the CWC is a bad treaty -- one that will likely increase risk of 
chemical warfare around the world."<p>
And with rogue states emboldened in the chemical weapons trade, can bolder terrorists be 
far behind?<p>
Meanwhile, the costs of the CWC run high for U.S. entrepreneurs and businesses, and 
therefore, for the economy in general.  The international bureaucratic mind runs wild thinking up 
all of the possible ways that chemicals, normally used in quite legitimate and beneficial ways, 
could be turned to perverse ends.  Hence, private, law-abiding industries right here in New York 
will become subject to regulations, paperwork, and inspections from an international agency 
headquartered in the Hague, Netherlands.  Indeed, this would be the first time that U.S. private 
industry confronts foreign inspections.<p>
However, chemical companies are not the only kinds of businesses exposed to the CWC. 
 Enterprises in the food, pharmaceutical, electronics, paint, petroleum, biotech, textiles, 
fertilizers, brewing, distilling, and other industries could be subject to CWC regulations.  
According to the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, more than 7,700 facilities in the U.S. are 
likely or possibly subject to the CWC.  In New York, the number stands at 560 facilities -- fourth 
highest among the states.<p>
New York businesses have long suffered from being beaten and battered by often 
senseless federal, state, and local regulations and taxes.  Adding new international regulatory 
burdens with a treaty that certainly does not serve, and may actually undermine national security, 
verges on madness.<p>
Make no mistake, the CWC creates formidable costs.  Time requirements to fill out the 
necessary paperwork on an annual basis range from an estimated 2.5 hours to 9.0 hours per 
chemical depending upon its classification, according to the U.S. Department of Commerce.  
Fines for non-compliance range up to $50,000 per incident.  Inspections will cost firms $10,000 
to $50,000 per visit.<p>
Naturally, all these costs weigh far more heavily on smaller businesses.  Small enterprises 
don't possess the requisite experience and resources to deal with increased regulatory burdens.  
Small, entrepreneurial firms, though, drive economic growth and job creation.  As we've long 
seen in New York, as entrepreneurs suffer, so does the economy.<p>
However, no matter how big or small, every business subject to CWC inspections will be 
exposed to the threat of international industrial espionage.  Opportunities to steal U.S. trade 
secrets will be numerous.  <p>
The CWC is a lose-lose treaty.  Costs run high, with absolutely no benefits in the end.  
The only way to prevent the danger of chemical weapons is to show those who might use them 
that the price for such atrocities will be quite dear.  <p>
Thirty-four Senate votes against ratification will kill the deeply flawed CWC, and salvage 
a bit of common sense in Congress.  Sixty-seven votes for the CWC and political symbolism 
wins out over substance once again.  <p>
Senators Moynihan and D'Amato, are you paying attention?<p>
<hr>
<i>Matthew Carolan is executive editor of National Review.  Raymond J. Keating serves as chief 
economist for the Small Business Survival Committee.</i>
<p><br>
