<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Keating's Corner</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><h2>
Keating's Corner</h2>
<P><br><b>
Addressing the Health Care "Crisis": Markets vs. Regulation
<p></b>
by Matthew Carolan and Raymond J. Keating	
<p>
<i>July 1, 1996</i>
<p><br>
<hr width="85%">
<p><br>
</center>
<blockquote>
We're all at least somewhat familiar with the demise of "Clinton-care."  Upon entering the White House, President and Mrs. Clinton quickly got to work manufacturing a health-care "crisis" in America.  And on that basis, the Clintons tried to seize government control over the health-care industry -- about 14 percent of the U.S. economy.  Their efforts failed as Americans realized that for all of its problems, we still have the best health-care system in the world.  Greater government controls only would have increased health-care costs -- both in terms of more dollars and rationed care.	New York serves as the perfect example.  The health insurance market is heavily regulated in the Empire State.  A 1993 community rating law (a one-size-fits-all government price control), for example, sent costs skyrocketing, pricing some 500,000 individuals out of the health insurance market.  
	Now a Republican-led Congress is moving forward on health-care reform using the failures of both Clinton-care and New York as models, but on a smaller scale.  Led by Senators Ted Kennedy, Democrat from neighboring Massachusetts, and Nancy Kassebaum, Republican from Kansas, health-care reform measures have passed both Houses of Congress with the differences now being hammered out quite publicly.  
	Problem number one is that the Kennedy-Kassebaum plan includes a guaranteed issue requirement.  Guaranteed issue requires insurance companies to supply health insurance to all individuals, with little regard to their medical history or current disposition.  As with most government intrusions into the marketplace, it sounds great at first blush.  However, a moment of reflection reveals that under such a plan individuals possess every incentive to avoid paying for health insurance until the last possible moment -- hiking costs for all insured consumers.  Where tried at the state level -- like in New York -- guaranteed-issue has boosted costs as well as the number of uninsured.	The Senate version of this reform effort also includes an amendment requiring that mental health be placed on par with physical health in insurance plans.  The mental health industry lobbied hard for this amendment.  Not able to keep costs under control, mental health providers want government to force consumption of their services.  
<P>
	The results from such a mandate are quite predictable, including higher costs.  Indeed, premiums are expected to increase between 4% and 12% and the Congressional Budget Office (CBO) estimates total direct costs to the employer-based insurance market at $11.6 billion.  Also, the loss of employer-provided health coverage stands as a real threat, with CBO placing the number of Americans likely to lose employer-sponsored health insurance at 800,000.  Other effects include reduced choices in terms of health plans, as well as lost benefits and wages to pay for the additional costs.  	This mental-health mandate is a response to another manufactured crisis.  Right now, 99 percent of employer-based health plans provide some mental health coverage.  So-called "parity" does not exist because mental health is a rather vague notion, offering clear opportunities for abuse, is less easily damaged, and can be very expensive to treat.	The mental-health parity mandate applies to state and local governments -- hiking costs for already overburdened New York taxpayers -- but excludes the federal government's Medicaid and Medicare programs.  The Senators did not want to deal with rising costs in their own programs.	
<P>
One saving grace exists in this current health-care reform effort.  The House version includes a tax-free medical savings account (MSA) provision.  MSAs address the true problems of portability and skyrocketing costs in health care.  The MSA option combines a savings account for health-care expenses and a catastrophic insurance plan.  The employer deposits funds in the employee's MSA each year and whatever is not spent, the employee keeps, but if expenses are higher, catastrophic insurance kicks in.	Everyone benefits under the MSA plan.  Experience at more than 3,000 companies across the U.S. that currently use MSAs (even without federal tax benefits) shows that choices increase and costs decline.  Individuals with both few and many health-care needs have voiced satisfaction.  And as for portability, it's the individual's MSA -- if you move jobs, your MSA moves with you.	
<P>
Broadening the use of MSAs by extending the same tax benefits currently enjoyed only by traditional employer-provided health plans will reduce costs throughout the health-care system.  The main impetus to rising costs in health care are third-party payments.  When either the government or an employer-provided health plan foots the bill, the consumer and supplier of health care services need not concern themselves with costs.  We're all familiar with the doctor giving sample medication to people without insurance, while he writes a prescription for $75 when some big insurance company or the government is paying.  Without the traditional buyer-seller relationship, costs naturally increase.  
<P>
	Congress should let Kennedy-Kassebaum die in conference, and instead, pass a clean MSA bill.  In the meantime, our New York officials should show some leadership and pass tax-free MSAs for New York.  Market choices must replace government micro-management of health care.
<P><br><center><i>
Matthew Carolan is executive editor for National Review.  Raymond J. Keating is chief economist with the Small Business Survival Committee.</i>
<p><br>
