<HEAD>
<TITLE>Keating's Corner</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><h2>
Keating's Corner</h2>
<P><br><b>
Recommended Reading for a New York Summer
<p></b>
by Matthew Carolan and Raymond J. Keating	
<p>
<i>June 10, 1996</i>
<p><br>
<hr width="85%">
<p><br>
</center>
<blockquote>
Summer is not only the season for barbecues, the beach, and golf; it remains ideal for reading a good book while sipping a cool drink.  We offer a few suggestions -- books both old and new -- generally in agreement with our conservative views.	First, we offer titles covering national issues.
<P>
<i>Why Government Doesn't Work</i> by Harry Browne (St. Martin's):  An eminently reasonable and readable book just out from the Libertarian candidate for president, explaining how government in the United States went from consuming 3 percent of every American's income in 1900, to 57 percent today (and growing!).
<P>
<i>The Seven Fat Years: And How To Do It Again</i> by Robert L. Bartley (Free Press):  Despite contrary declarations from establishment economists, the Clinton Administration, and much of the media, the U.S. economy is slogging along at an anemic rate of growth.  Bartley not only reveals the policies that lead to robust economic growth and real opportunity, but manages to turn economics into an interesting read.
<P>
<i>Lost Rights</i> by James Bovard (St. Martin's)  Bovard shocks the reader with case after case of law-abiding Americans killed, injured, left unemployed, or without property through the arrogance of our federal government. Keep the Rolaids handy when you read this one. 
<P>
<i>Atlas Shrugged</i> by Ayn Rand (Signet):  This is simply a great work of fiction.  Everyone we know who has read this book says the same thing about it; "It's happening now!"  Rand's huge novel about a mid-20th century America gone mad for economic "fairness" is chilling in its similarities to current events and attitudes among Americans. One overlong, didactic speech (about 50 pages) toward the end tires the reader, but otherwise this is a life-changing read.
<P>
<i>A Good Walk Spoiled</i> by John Feinstein (Little Brown):  This book has nothing to do with politics or economics, it is just a wonderful account of life on the PGA Tour.	Of course, several tomes addressing New York are well worth reading while relaxing in the shade.
<P>
<i>The Rockefellers</i> by Peter Collier and David Horowitz (Holt):  This book has been out of print, so check your library or track it down at a used book store.  A fascinating account of the family that gave us Nelson Rockefeller -- who as governor did more damage to the economy of New York than any other individual in history.
<P>
<i>Senator Pothole</i> by Leonard Lurie (Birch Lane):  Chronicles the rise to power, through Nassau County's sleazy Republican machine, of New York's junior Senator, Al D'Amato.  A bit heavy on detail, but otherwise a clear assessment of everything that is wrong with government serving the interests of the political clubhouse.  
<P>
<i>The Unmaking of a Mayor</i> by William F. Buckley, Jr. (Viking Press): Another out-of-print book worth tracking down.  A fascinating, depressing, and often hilarious account of William F. Buckley Jr.'s run for mayor of New York City in 1965, which effectively put an end to golden-boy liberal Republican John Lindsey's aspirations for higher office.  Nothing has changed in New York City, as this book shows.
<P>
<i>The Power Broker: Robert Moses and the Fall of New York</i> by Robert Caro (Vintage Books):  A Pulitzer-Prize winner detailing the politics of New York State and City -- a fascinating account of arrogance, power, and government run amok.
<P>
<i>The House of Morgan</i> by Ron Chernow (Atlantic Monthly Press):  A fine read about the history of one of New York's great banking houses.  Chernow exhibits an understanding of history, politics and economics, and writes well -- a rare combination. 
<i>Plunkitt of Tammany Hall</i> by William I. Riordan (Dutton): This requires another trip to the library for a classic on the men who wrote the book on New York political corruption.
<P>
<i>The Encyclopedia of New York City</i> edited by Kenneth Jackson (Yale University):  This weighty, oversized, 1,350-page encyclopedia is not easily dragged to the beach, but it should sit at the side of your favorite armchair to be thumbed through during the summer months.  Almost everything you ever wanted to know -- or haven't even thought of -- about New York City is included.  We simply consider it invaluable.	
<P>
Finally, when additional breaks from public policy are in order, we turn to baseball.  As the Yankees compete for the pennant, we recommend another oversized tome -- <i>The Yankee Encyclopedia</i> by Mark Gallagher (Sagamore Publishing).  Stats, player biographies, history of the Stadium, season summaries -- it's all there for an informative summer about the most storied franchise of our national pastime.
<P>
<br><center>
<i>Matthew Carolan is executive editor of National Review.  Raymond J. Keating serves as chief economist for the Small Business Survival Committee.</i>
<p><br>
| <a href="/sbsc/corner/corner.html">Keating's Corner</a> |</center>
